# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: simd-hardware
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:simd-hardware/advanced-vector-extensions] AVX-512 expands AVX to 512-bit support using a new EVEX prefix encoding proposed by Intel in July 2013 and first supported by Intel with the Knights Landing co-processor, which shipped in 2016.
[src:simd-hardware/advanced-vector-extensions] In conventional processors, AVX-512 was introduced with Skylake server and HEDT processors in 2017.
[src:simd-hardware/advanced-vector-extensions] AVX uses sixteen YMM registers to perform a single instruction on multiple pieces of data (see SIMD).
[src:simd-hardware/advanced-vector-extensions] The width of the SIMD registers is increased from 128 bits to 256 bits, and renamed from XMM0–XMM7 to YMM0–YMM7 (in x86-64 mode, from XMM0–XMM15 to YMM0–YMM15).
[src:simd-hardware/advanced-vector-extensions] The legacy SSE instructions can still be utilized via the VEX prefix to operate on the lower 128 bits of the YMM registers.
[src:simd-hardware/advanced-vector-extensions] AVX introduces a three-operand SIMD instruction format called VEX coding scheme, where the destination register is distinct from the two source operands.
[src:simd-hardware/advanced-vector-extensions] For example, an SSE instruction using the conventional two-operand form *a* ← *a* + *b* can now use a non-destructive three-operand form *c* ← *a* + *b*, preserving both source operands.
[src:simd-hardware/advanced-vector-extensions] Originally, AVX's three-operand format was limited to the instructions with SIMD operands (YMM), and did not include instructions with general purpose registers (e.g.
[src:simd-hardware/advanced-vector-extensions] It was later used for coding new instructions on general purpose registers in later extensions, such as BMI.
[src:simd-hardware/advanced-vector-extensions] VEX coding is also used for instructions operating on the k0-k7 mask registers that were introduced with AVX-512.
[src:simd-hardware/advanced-vector-extensions] The alignment requirement of SIMD memory operands is relaxed.
[src:simd-hardware/advanced-vector-extensions] Unlike their non-VEX coded counterparts, most VEX coded vector instructions no longer require their memory operands to be aligned to the vector size.
[src:simd-hardware/advanced-vector-extensions] Notably, the `VMOVDQA` instruction still requires its memory operand to be aligned.
[src:simd-hardware/advanced-vector-extensions] The new VEX coding scheme introduces a new set of code prefixes that extends the opcode space, allows instructions to have more than two operands, and allows SIMD vector registers to be longer than 128 bits.
[src:simd-hardware/advanced-vector-extensions] The VEX prefix can also be used on the legacy SSE instructions giving them a three-operand form, and making them interact more efficiently with AVX instructions without the need for `VZEROUPPER` and `VZEROALL`.
[src:simd-hardware/advanced-vector-extensions] The AVX instructions support both 128-bit and 256-bit SIMD.
[src:simd-hardware/advanced-vector-extensions] The 128-bit versions can be useful to improve old code without needing to widen the vectorization, and avoid the penalty of going from SSE to AVX; they are also faster on some early AMD implementations of AVX.
[src:simd-hardware/advanced-vector-extensions] This mode is sometimes known as AVX-128.
[src:simd-hardware/advanced-vector-extensions] Compared to SSE series, AVX further enhanced performance for digital media playback, web browsing, asymmetric encryption, and others.
[src:simd-hardware/advanced-vector-extensions] These AVX instructions are in addition to the ones that are 256-bit extensions of the legacy 128-bit SSE instructions; most are usable on both 128-bit and 256-bit operands.
[src:simd-hardware/advanced-vector-extensions] Issues regarding compatibility between future Intel and AMD processors are discussed under XOP instruction set.
[src:simd-hardware/advanced-vector-extensions] AVX adds new register-state through the 256-bit wide YMM register file, so explicit operating system support is required to properly save and restore AVX's expanded registers between context switches.
[src:simd-hardware/advanced-vector-extensions] Advanced Vector Extensions 2 (AVX2), also known as **Haswell New Instructions**, is an expansion of the AVX instruction set introduced in Intel's Haswell microarchitecture.
[src:simd-hardware/advanced-vector-extensions] Sometimes three-operand fused multiply-accumulate (FMA3) extension is considered part of AVX2, as it was introduced by Intel in the same processor microarchitecture.
[src:simd-hardware/advanced-vector-extensions] This is a separate extension using its own CPUID flag, described on its own page and not below.
[src:simd-hardware/advanced-vector-extensions] AVX-512 instructions are encoded with the new EVEX prefix.
[src:simd-hardware/advanced-vector-extensions] It allows 4 operands, 8 new 64-bit opmask registers, scalar memory mode with automatic broadcast, explicit rounding control, and compressed displacement memory addressing mode.
[src:simd-hardware/advanced-vector-extensions] The width of the register file is increased to 512 bits and total register count increased to 32 (registers ZMM0-ZMM31) in x86-64 mode.
[src:simd-hardware/advanced-vector-extensions] AVX-512 consists of multiple instruction subsets, not all of which are meant to be supported by all processors implementing them.
[src:simd-hardware/advanced-vector-extensions] Only the core extension AVX-512F (AVX-512 Foundation) is required by all implementations, though all current implementations also support CD (conflict detection).
[src:simd-hardware/advanced-vector-extensions] All central processors with AVX-512 also support VL, DQ and BW.
[src:simd-hardware/advanced-vector-extensions] The ER, PF, 4VNNIW and 4FMAPS instruction set extensions are currently only implemented in Intel computing coprocessors.
[src:simd-hardware/advanced-vector-extensions] The updated SSE/AVX instructions in AVX-512F use the same mnemonics as AVX versions; they can operate on 512-bit ZMM registers, and will also support 128/256 bit XMM/YMM registers (with AVX-512VL) and byte, word, doubleword and quadword integer operands (with AVX-512BW/DQ and VBMI).
[src:simd-hardware/advanced-vector-extensions] AVX-VNNI is a VEX-coded variant of the AVX512-VNNI instruction set extension.
[src:simd-hardware/advanced-vector-extensions] Similarly, AVX-IFMA is a VEX-coded variant of AVX512-IFMA.
[src:simd-hardware/advanced-vector-extensions] These extensions provide the same sets of operations as their AVX-512 counterparts, but are limited to 256-bit vectors and do not support any additional features of EVEX encoding, such as broadcasting, opmask registers or accessing more than 16 vector registers.
[src:simd-hardware/advanced-vector-extensions] These extensions allow for supporting VNNI and IFMA operations even when AVX-512 is not implemented in the processor.
[src:simd-hardware/advanced-vector-extensions] AVX-NE-CONVERT introduces a set of instructions for converting between Bfloat16 (BF16), half-precision (FP16) and single-precision (FP32) floating-point numbers.
[src:simd-hardware/advanced-vector-extensions] The new instructions are VEX-coded, and therefore are limited to AVX2 vector registers and lack opmask support from AVX-512.
[src:simd-hardware/advanced-vector-extensions] Broadcast is only supported by means of two special instructions for loading numbers from memory, it is not supported as an instruction encoding feature.
[src:simd-hardware/advanced-vector-extensions] These instruction sets further extend the AVX-VNNI extension by adding support for more combinations of input data types for the `VPDP*` series of instructions.
[src:simd-hardware/advanced-vector-extensions] Where `VPDPBUSD(S)` instructions from AVX-VNNI take a vector of unsigned bytes as the first input operand and a vector of signed bytes as the second input operand, AVX-VNNI-INT8 adds variants of these instructions that support signed and unsigned byte inputs at any position.
[src:simd-hardware/advanced-vector-extensions] Similarly, where `VPDPWSSD(S)` from AVX-VNNI take two vectors of signed 16-bit words as input operands, AVX-VNNI-INT16 adds support for signed and unsigned 16-bit word inputs at any position.
[src:simd-hardware/advanced-vector-extensions] For the instructions accepting signed and unsigned inputs, there are distinct instructions for the two possible orders of inputs (signed/unsigned and unsigned/signed) because VEX encoding only supports the second input operand to be a memory operand.
[src:simd-hardware/advanced-vector-extensions] This allows any of the supported data types to be loaded from memory by the instruction.
[src:simd-hardware/advanced-vector-extensions] AVX10, announced in July 2023, is a new, "converged" AVX instruction set.
[src:simd-hardware/advanced-vector-extensions] It addresses several issues of AVX-512; in particular, that it is split into too many parts (20 feature flags).
[src:simd-hardware/advanced-vector-extensions] The initial technical paper also made 512-bit vectors optional to support, but as of revision 3.0, vector length enumeration is removed and 512-bit vectors are mandatory.
[src:simd-hardware/advanced-vector-extensions] AVX10 presents a simplified CPUID interface to test for instruction support, consisting of the AVX10 version number (indicating the set of instructions supported, with later versions always being a superset of an earlier one).
[src:simd-hardware/advanced-vector-extensions] For example, AVX10.2 indicates that a CPU is capable of the second version of AVX10.
[src:simd-hardware/advanced-vector-extensions] Initial revisions of the AVX10 technical specifications also included maximum supported vector length as part of the ISA extension name, e.g.
[src:simd-hardware/advanced-vector-extensions] AVX10.2/256 would mean a second version of AVX10 with vector length up to 256 bits, but later revisions made that unnecessary.
[src:simd-hardware/advanced-vector-extensions] The first version of AVX10, notated AVX10.1, does *not* introduce any instructions or encoding features beyond what is already in AVX-512 (specifically, in Intel Sapphire Rapids: AVX-512F, CD, VL, DQ, BW, IFMA, VBMI, VBMI2, BITALG, VNNI, GFNI, VPOPCNTDQ, VPCLMULQDQ, VAES, BF16, FP16).
[src:simd-hardware/advanced-vector-extensions] For CPUs supporting AVX10 and 512-bit vectors, all legacy AVX-512 feature flags will remain set to facilitate applications supporting AVX-512 to continue using AVX-512 instructions.
[src:simd-hardware/advanced-vector-extensions] AVX10.1 was first released in Intel Granite Rapids (Q3 2024) and AVX10.2 will be available in Diamond Rapids and Nova Lake.
[src:simd-hardware/advanced-vector-extensions] Since AVX instructions are wider, they consume more power and generate more heat.
[src:simd-hardware/advanced-vector-extensions] Executing heavy AVX instructions at high CPU clock frequencies may affect CPU stability due to excessive voltage droop during load transients.
[src:simd-hardware/advanced-vector-extensions] Some Intel processors have provisions to reduce the Turbo Boost frequency limit when such instructions are being executed.
[src:simd-hardware/advanced-vector-extensions] This reduction happens even if the CPU hasn't reached its thermal and power consumption limits.
[src:simd-hardware/advanced-vector-extensions] The frequency transition can be soft or hard.
[src:simd-hardware/advanced-vector-extensions] Hard transition means the frequency is reduced as soon as such an instruction is spotted; soft transition means that the frequency is reduced only after reaching a threshold number of matching instructions.
[src:simd-hardware/advanced-vector-extensions] Rocket Lake processors do not trigger frequency reduction upon executing any kind of vector instructions regardless of the vector size.
[src:simd-hardware/advanced-vector-extensions] However, downclocking can still happen due to other reasons, such as reaching thermal and power limits.
[src:simd-hardware/advanced-vector-extensions] Downclocking means that using AVX in a mixed workload with an Intel processor can incur a frequency penalty.
[src:simd-hardware/advanced-vector-extensions] Avoiding the use of wide and heavy instructions help minimize the impact in these cases.
[src:simd-hardware/advanced-vector-extensions] AVX-512VL allows for using 256-bit or 128-bit operands in AVX-512 instructions, making it a sensible default for mixed loads.
[src:simd-hardware/advanced-vector-extensions] On supported and unlocked variants of processors that down-clock, the clock ratio reduction offsets (typically called AVX and AVX-512 offsets) are adjustable and may be turned off entirely (set to 0x) via Intel's Overclocking / Tuning utility or in BIOS if supported there.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] Due to their low costs, low power consumption, and low heat generation, ARM processors are useful for light, portable, battery-powered devices, including smartphones, laptops, and tablet computers, as well as embedded systems.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] However, ARM processors are also used for desktops and servers, including Fugaku, the world's fastest supercomputer from 2020 to 2022.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] With over 230 billion ARM chips produced, since at least 2003, and with its dominance increasing every year, ARM is the most widely used family of instruction set architectures.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] There have been several generations of the ARM design.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] The original ARM1 used a 32-bit internal structure but had a 26-bit address space that limited it to 64 MB of main memory.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] This limitation was removed in the ARMv3 series, which has a 32-bit address space, and several additional generations up to ARMv7 remained 32-bit.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] Released in 2011, the ARMv8-A architecture added support for a 64-bit address space and 64-bit arithmetic with its new 32-bit fixed-length instruction set.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] Arm Holdings has also released a series of additional instruction sets for different roles: the "Thumb" extensions add both 32- and 16-bit instructions for improved code density, while Jazelle added instructions for directly handling Java bytecode.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] More recent changes include the addition of simultaneous multithreading (SMT) for improved performance or fault tolerance.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] Acorn Computers' first widely successful design was the BBC Micro, introduced in December 1981.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] This was a relatively conventional machine based on the MOS Technology 6502 CPU but ran at roughly double the performance of competing designs like the Apple II due to its use of faster dynamic random-access memory (DRAM).
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] Typical DRAM of the era ran at about 2 MHz; Acorn arranged a deal with Hitachi for a supply of faster 4 MHz parts.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] Machines of the era generally shared memory between the processor and the framebuffer, which allowed the processor to quickly update the contents of the screen without having to perform separate input/output (I/O).
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] As the timing of the video display is exacting, the video hardware had to have priority access to that memory.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] Due to a quirk of the 6502's design, the CPU left the memory untouched for half of the time.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] Thus by running the CPU at 1 MHz, the video system could read data during those down times, taking up the total 2 MHz bandwidth of the RAM.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] In the BBC Micro, the use of 4 MHz RAM allowed the same technique to be used, but running at twice the speed.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] This allowed it to outperform any similar machine on the market.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] 1981 was also the year that the IBM Personal Computer was introduced.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] Using the recently introduced Intel 8088, a 16-bit CPU compared to the 6502's 8-bit design, it offered higher overall performance.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] Its introduction changed the desktop computer market radically: what had been largely a hobby and gaming market emerging over the prior five years began to change to a must-have business tool where the earlier 8-bit designs simply could not compete.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] Even newer 32-bit designs were also coming to market, such as the Motorola 68000 and National Semiconductor NS32016.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] Acorn began considering how to compete in this market and produced a new paper design named the Acorn Business Computer.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] They set themselves the goal of producing a machine with ten times the performance of the BBC Micro, but at the same price.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] This would outperform and underprice the PC.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] At the same time, the recent introduction of the Apple Lisa brought the graphical user interface (GUI) concept to a wider audience and suggested the future belonged to machines with a GUI.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] The Lisa, however, cost $9,995, as it was packed with support chips, large amounts of memory, and a hard disk drive, all very expensive then.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] The engineers then began studying all of the CPU designs available.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] Their conclusion about the existing 16-bit designs was that they were a lot more expensive and were still "a bit crap", offering only slightly higher performance than their BBC Micro design.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] They also almost always demanded a large number of support chips to operate even at that level, which drove up the cost of the computer as a whole.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] These systems would simply not hit the design goal.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] They also considered the new 32-bit designs, but these cost even more and had the same issues with support chips.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] According to Sophie Wilson, all the processors tested at that time performed about the same, with about a 4 Mbit/s bandwidth.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] Two key events led Acorn down the path to ARM.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] One was the publication of a series of reports from the University of California, Berkeley, which suggested that a simple chip design could nevertheless have extremely high performance, much higher than the latest 32-bit designs on the market.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] The second was a visit by Steve Furber and Sophie Wilson to the Western Design Center, a company run by Bill Mensch and his sister Kathryn, which had become the logical successor to the MOS team and was offering new versions like the WDC 65C02.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] The Acorn team saw high school students producing chip layouts on Apple II machines, which suggested that anyone could do it.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] In contrast, a visit to another design firm working on modern 32-bit CPU revealed a team with over a dozen members who were already on revision H of their design and yet it still contained bugs.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] This cemented their late 1983 decision to begin their own CPU design, the Acorn RISC Machine.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] The original Berkeley RISC designs were in some sense teaching systems, not designed specifically for outright performance.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] To the RISC's basic register-heavy and load/store concepts, ARM added a number of the well-received design notes of the 6502.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] Primary among them was the ability to quickly service interrupts, which allowed the machines to offer reasonable input/output performance with no added external hardware.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] To offer interrupts with similar performance as the 6502, the ARM design limited its physical address space to 64 MB of total addressable space, requiring 26 bits of address.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] As instructions were 4 bytes (32 bits) long, and required to be aligned on 4-byte boundaries, the lower 2 bits of an instruction address were always zero.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] This meant the program counter (PC) only needed to be 24 bits, allowing it to be stored along with the eight bit processor flags in a single 32-bit register.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] That meant that upon receiving an interrupt, the entire machine state could be saved in a single operation, whereas had the PC been a full 32-bit value, it would require separate operations to store the PC and the status flags.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] This decision halved the interrupt overhead.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] Another change, and among the most important in terms of practical real-world performance, was the modification of the instruction set to take advantage of page mode DRAM.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] Recently introduced, page mode allowed subsequent accesses of memory to run twice as fast if they were roughly in the same location, or "page", in the DRAM chip.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] Berkeley's design did not consider page mode and treated all memory equally.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] The ARM design added special vector-like memory access instructions, the "S-cycles", that could be used to fill or save multiple registers in a single page using page mode.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] This doubled memory performance when they could be used, and was especially important for graphics performance.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] The Berkeley RISC designs used register windows to reduce the number of register saves and restores performed in procedure calls; the ARM design did not adopt this.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] Wilson developed the instruction set, writing a simulation of the processor in BBC BASIC that ran on a BBC Micro with a second 6502 processor.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] This convinced Acorn engineers they were on the right track.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] Wilson approached Acorn's CEO, Hermann Hauser, and requested more resources.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] Hauser gave his approval and assembled a small team to design the actual processor based on Wilson's instruction set architecture.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] The official Acorn RISC Machine project started in October 1983.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] Acorn chose VLSI Technology as the "silicon partner", as they were a source of ROMs and custom chips for Acorn.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] Acorn provided the design and VLSI provided the layout and production.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] The first samples of ARM silicon worked properly when first received and tested on 26 April 1985.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] Known as ARM1, these versions ran at 6 MHz.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] The first ARM application was as a second processor for the BBC Micro, where it helped in developing simulation software to finish development of the support chips (VIDC, IOC, MEMC), and sped up the CAD software used in ARM2 development.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] Wilson subsequently rewrote BBC BASIC in ARM assembly language.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] The in-depth knowledge gained from designing the instruction set enabled the code to be very dense, making ARM BBC BASIC an extremely good test for any ARM emulator.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] ARM Evaluations Systems featuring ARM1 CPUs and supplied as second processors for BBC Micro and Master machines, were made available from July 1986 under the Acorn OEM Products brand to developers and researchers.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] The A500 Second Processor, an additional ARM1 based BBC Micro and Master second processor, featured the ARM support chipset (VIDC, IOC, MEMC), was capable of producing video output and operating near independently of the host BBC Micro.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] The result of the simulations on the ARM1 boards led to the late 1986 introduction of the ARM2 design running at 8 MHz, and the early 1987 speed-bumped version at 10 to 12 MHz.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] A significant change in the underlying architecture was the addition of a Booth multiplier, whereas formerly multiplication had to be carried out in software.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] Further, a new Fast Interrupt reQuest mode, FIQ for short, allowed registers 8 to 14 to be replaced as part of the interrupt itself.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] This meant FIQ requests did not have to save out their registers, further speeding interrupts.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] The first use of the ARM2 was in internal Acorn A500 development machines, and the Acorn Archimedes personal computer models A305, A310, and A440, launched on the 6th June 1987.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] According to the Dhrystone benchmark, the ARM2 was roughly seven times the performance of a typical 7 MHz 68000-based system like the Amiga or Macintosh SE.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] It was twice as fast as an Intel 80386 running at 16 MHz, and about the same speed as a multi-processor VAX-11/784 superminicomputer.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] The only systems that beat it were the Sun SPARC and MIPS R2000 RISC-based workstations.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] Further, as the CPU was designed for high-speed I/O, it dispensed with many of the support chips seen in these machines; notably, it lacked any dedicated direct memory access (DMA) controller which was often found on workstations.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] The graphics system was also simplified based on the same set of underlying assumptions about memory and timing.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] The result was a dramatically simplified design, offering performance on par with expensive workstations but at a price point similar to contemporary desktops.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] The ARM2 featured a 32-bit data bus, 26-bit address space and 27 32-bit registers, of which 16 are accessible at any one time (including the PC).
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] The ARM2 had a transistor count of just 30,000, compared to Motorola's six-year-older 68000 model with around 68,000.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] Much of this simplicity came from the lack of microcode, which represents about one-quarter to one-third of the 68000's transistors, and the lack of (like most CPUs of the day) a cache.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] This simplicity enabled the ARM2 to have a low power consumption and simpler thermal packaging by having fewer powered transistors.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] Nevertheless, ARM2 offered better performance than the contemporary 1987 IBM PS/2 Model 50, which initially utilised an Intel 80286, offering 1.8 MIPS @ 10 MHz, and later in 1987, the 2 MIPS of the PS/2 70, with its Intel 386 DX @ 16 MHz.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] A successor, ARM3, was produced with a 4 KB cache, which further improved performance.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] The address bus was extended to 32 bits in the ARM6, but program code still had to lie within the first 64 MB of memory in 26-bit compatibility mode, due to the reserved bits for the status flags.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] In 1988, Sanyo became a worldwide second source for the ARM2 and associated chipset under an agreement with VLSI Technology.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] In the late 1980s, Apple Computer and VLSI Technology started working with Acorn on newer versions of the ARM core.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] In 1990, Acorn spun off the design team into a new company named Advanced RISC Machines Ltd., which became ARM Ltd. when its parent company, Arm Holdings plc, floated on the London Stock Exchange and Nasdaq in 1998.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] The new Apple–ARM work would eventually evolve into the ARM6, first released in early 1992.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] Apple used the ARM6-based ARM610 as the basis for their Apple Newton PDA.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] In 1994, Acorn used the ARM610 as the main central processing unit (CPU) in their RiscPC computers.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] DEC licensed the ARMv4 architecture and produced the StrongARM.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] At 233 MHz, this CPU drew only one watt (newer versions draw far less).
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] This work was later passed to Intel as part of a lawsuit settlement, and Intel took the opportunity to supplement their i960 line with the StrongARM.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] Intel later developed its own high performance implementation named XScale, which it has since sold to Marvell.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] Transistor count of the ARM core remained essentially the same throughout these changes; ARM2 had 30,000 transistors, while ARM6 grew only to 35,000.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] In 2005, about 98% of all mobile phones sold used at least one ARM processor.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] In 2010, producers of chips based on ARM architectures reported shipments of 6.1 billion ARM-based processors, representing 95% of smartphones, 35% of digital televisions and set-top boxes, and 10% of mobile computers.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] In 2011, the 32-bit ARM architecture was the most widely used architecture in mobile devices and the most popular 32-bit one in embedded systems.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] In 2013, 10 billion were produced and "ARM-based chips are found in nearly 60 percent of the world's mobile devices".
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] Arm Holdings's primary business is selling IP cores, which licensees use to create microcontrollers (MCUs), CPUs, and systems-on-chips based on those cores.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] The original design manufacturer combines the ARM core with other parts to produce a complete device, typically one that can be built in existing semiconductor fabrication plants (fabs) at low cost and still deliver substantial performance.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] The most successful implementation has been the ARM7TDMI with hundreds of millions sold.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] Atmel has been a precursor design center in the ARM7TDMI-based embedded system.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] The ARM architectures used in smartphones, PDAs and other mobile devices range from ARMv5 to ARMv8-A.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] In 2009, some manufacturers introduced netbooks based on ARM architecture CPUs, in direct competition with netbooks based on Intel Atom.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] Arm Holdings offers a variety of licensing terms, varying in cost and deliverables.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] Arm Holdings provides to all licensees an integratable hardware description of the ARM core as well as complete software development toolset (compiler, debugger, software development kit), and the right to sell manufactured silicon containing the ARM CPU.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] SoC packages integrating ARM's core designs include Nvidia Tegra's first three generations, CSR plc's Quatro family, ST-Ericsson's Nova and NovaThor, Silicon Labs's Precision32 MCU, Texas Instruments's OMAP products, Samsung's Hummingbird and Exynos products, Apple's A4, A5, and A5X, and NXP's i.MX.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] Fabless licensees, who wish to integrate an ARM core into their own chip design, are usually only interested in acquiring a ready-to-manufacture verified semiconductor intellectual property core.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] For these customers, Arm Holdings delivers a gate netlist description of the chosen ARM core, along with an abstracted simulation model and test programs to aid design integration and verification.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] More ambitious customers, including integrated device manufacturers (IDM) and foundry operators, choose to acquire the processor IP in synthesizable RTL (Verilog) form.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] With the synthesizable RTL, the customer has the ability to perform architectural level optimisations and extensions.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] This allows the designer to achieve exotic design goals not otherwise possible with an unmodified netlist (high clock speed, very low power consumption, instruction set extensions, etc.).
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] While Arm Holdings does not grant the licensee the right to resell the ARM architecture itself, licensees may freely sell manufactured products such as chip devices, evaluation boards and complete systems.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] Merchant foundries can be a special case; not only are they allowed to sell finished silicon containing ARM cores, they generally hold the right to re-manufacture ARM cores for other customers.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] Arm Holdings prices its IP based on perceived value.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] Lower performing ARM cores typically have lower licence costs than higher performing cores.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] In implementation terms, a synthesisable core costs more than a hard macro (blackbox) core.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] Complicating price matters, a merchant foundry that holds an ARM licence, such as Samsung or Fujitsu, can offer fab customers reduced licensing costs.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] In exchange for acquiring the ARM core through the foundry's in-house design services, the customer can reduce or eliminate payment of ARM's upfront licence fee.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] Compared to dedicated semiconductor foundries (such as TSMC and UMC) without in-house design services, Fujitsu/Samsung charge two- to three-times more per manufactured wafer.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] For low to mid volume applications, a design service foundry offers lower overall pricing (through subsidisation of the licence fee).
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] For high volume mass-produced parts, the long term cost reduction achievable through lower wafer pricing reduces the impact of ARM's NRE (non-recurring engineering) costs, making the dedicated foundry a better choice.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] In February 2016, ARM announced the Built on ARM Cortex Technology licence, often shortened to Built on Cortex (BoC) licence.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] This licence allows companies to partner with ARM and make modifications to ARM Cortex designs.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] These design modifications will not be shared with other companies.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] These semi-custom core designs also have brand freedom, for example Kryo 280.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] Companies that are current licensees of Built on ARM Cortex Technology include Qualcomm.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] Companies can also obtain an ARM *architectural licence* for designing their own CPU cores using the ARM instruction sets.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] These cores must comply fully with the ARM architecture.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] Companies that have designed cores that implement an ARM architecture include Apple, AppliedMicro (now: Ampere Computing), Broadcom, Cavium (now: Marvell), Digital Equipment Corporation, Intel, Nvidia, Qualcomm, Samsung Electronics, Fujitsu, and NUVIA Inc.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] On 16 July 2019, ARM announced ARM Flexible Access.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] ARM Flexible Access provides unlimited access to included ARM intellectual property (IP) for development.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] Per product licence fees are required once a customer reaches foundry tapeout or prototyping.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] 75% of ARM's most recent IP over the last two years are included in ARM Flexible Access.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] ARMv3 included a compatibility mode to support the 26-bit addresses of earlier versions of the architecture.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] This compatibility mode is *optional* in ARMv4, and removed entirely in ARMv5.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] Arm provides a list of vendors who implement ARM cores in their design (application specific standard products (ASSP), microprocessor and microcontrollers).
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] ARM cores are used in a number of products, particularly PDAs and smartphones.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] Some computing examples are Microsoft's first generation Surface, Surface 2 and Pocket PC devices (following 2002), Apple's iPads, and Asus's Eee Pad Transformer tablet computers, and several Chromebook laptops.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] Others include Apple's iPhone smartphones and iPod portable media players, Canon PowerShot digital cameras, Nintendo Switch hybrid, the Wii security processor and 3DS handheld game consoles, and TomTom turn-by-turn navigation systems.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] In 2005, Arm took part in the development of Manchester University's computer SpiNNaker, which used ARM cores to simulate the human brain.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p01] ARM chips are also used in Raspberry Pi, BeagleBoard, BeagleBone, PandaBoard, and other single-board computers, because they are very small, inexpensive, and consume very little power.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] The 32-bit ARM architecture (**ARM32**), such as **ARMv7-A** (implementing AArch32; see section on Armv8-A for more on it), was the most widely used architecture in mobile devices as of 2011.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] Although the architecture profiles were first defined for ARMv7, ARM subsequently defined the ARMv6-M architecture (used by the Cortex M0/M0+/M1) as a subset of the ARMv7-M profile with fewer instructions.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] 26-bit addressing - obsolete as of June 2000.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] Multiply and multiply-accumulate instructions; coprocessor support - all variants obsolete as of June 2000.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] 32-bit addressing - all variants obsolete as of July 2005.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] , the former of which supports the 32-bit ARM instruction set, called A32, and the Thumb-2 instruction set, called T32, and the latter of which supports a new instruction set with 32 64-bit registers, called A64.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] Except in the M-profile, the 32-bit ARM architecture specifies several CPU modes, depending on the implemented architecture features.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] At any moment in time, the CPU can be in only one mode, but it can switch modes due to external events (interrupts) or programmatically.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] The original ARM implementation was hardwired without microcode, like the much simpler 8-bit 6502 processor used in prior Acorn microcomputers.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] ARM includes integer arithmetic operations for add, subtract, and multiply; some versions of the architecture also support divide operations.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] ARM supports 32-bit × 32-bit multiplies with either a 32-bit result or 64-bit result, though Cortex-M0 / M0+ / M1 cores do not support 64-bit results.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] Some ARM cores also support 16-bit × 16-bit and 32-bit × 16-bit multiplies.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] Registers R0 through R7 are the same across all CPU modes; they are never banked.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] Registers R8 through R12 are the same across all CPU modes except FIQ mode.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] FIQ mode has its own distinct R8 through R12 registers.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] R13 and R14 are banked across all privileged CPU modes except system mode.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] That is, each mode that can be entered because of an exception has its own R13 and R14.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] These registers generally contain the stack pointer and the return address from function calls, respectively.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] The Current Program Status Register (CPSR) has the following 32 bits.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] Almost every ARM instruction has a conditional execution feature called predication, which is implemented with a 4-bit condition code selector (the predicate).
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] To allow for unconditional execution, one of the four-bit codes causes the instruction to be always executed.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] Most other CPU architectures only have condition codes on branch instructions.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] Though the predicate takes up four of the 32 bits in an instruction code, and thus cuts down significantly on the encoding bits available for displacements in memory access instructions, it avoids branch instructions when generating code for small `if` statements.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] Apart from eliminating the branch instructions themselves, this preserves the fetch/decode/execute pipeline at the cost of only one cycle per skipped instruction.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] An algorithm that provides a good example of conditional execution is the subtraction-based Euclidean algorithm for computing the greatest common divisor.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] which avoids the branches around the `then` and `else` clauses.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] If `r0` and `r1` are equal then neither of the `SUB` instructions will be executed, eliminating the need for a conditional branch to implement the `while` check at the top of the loop, for example had `SUBLE` (less than or equal) been used.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] One of the ways that Thumb code provides a more dense encoding is to remove the four-bit selector from non-branch instructions.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] This results in the typical ARM program being denser than expected with fewer memory accesses; thus the pipeline is used more efficiently.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] The ARM processor also has features rarely seen in other RISC architectures, such as PC-relative addressing (indeed, on the 32-bit ARM the PC is one of its 16 registers) and pre- and post-increment addressing modes.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] The ARM instruction set has increased over time.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] Some early ARM processors (before ARM7TDMI), for example, have no instruction to store a two-byte quantity.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] The ARM7 and earlier implementations have a three-stage pipeline; the stages being fetch, decode, and execute.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] Higher-performance designs, such as the ARM9, have deeper pipelines: Cortex-A8 has thirteen stages.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] Additional implementation changes for higher performance include a faster adder and more extensive branch prediction logic.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] The difference between the ARM7DI and ARM7DMI cores, for example, was an improved multiplier; hence the added "M".
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] The ARM architecture (pre-Armv8) provides a non-intrusive way of extending the instruction set using "coprocessors" that can be addressed using MCR, MRC, MRRC, MCRR, and similar instructions.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] The coprocessor space is divided logically into 16 coprocessors with numbers from 0 to 15, coprocessor 15 (cp15) being reserved for some typical control functions like managing the caches and MMU operation on processors that have one.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] In ARM-based machines, peripheral devices are usually attached to the processor by mapping their physical registers into ARM memory space, into the coprocessor space, or by connecting to another device (a bus) that in turn attaches to the processor.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] Coprocessor accesses have lower latency, so some peripherals—for example, an XScale interrupt controller—are accessible in both ways: through memory and through coprocessors.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] In other cases, chip designers only integrate hardware using the coprocessor mechanism.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] For example, an image processing engine might be a small ARM7TDMI core combined with a coprocessor that has specialised operations to support a specific set of HDTV transcoding primitives.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] All modern ARM processors include hardware debugging facilities, allowing software debuggers to perform operations such as halting, stepping, and breakpointing of code starting from reset.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] These facilities are built using JTAG support, though some newer cores optionally support ARM's own two-wire "SWD" protocol.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] In ARM7TDMI cores, the "D" represented JTAG debug support, and the "I" represented presence of an "EmbeddedICE" debug module.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] For ARM7 and ARM9 core generations, EmbeddedICE over JTAG was a de facto debug standard, though not architecturally guaranteed.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] The ARMv7 architecture defines basic debug facilities at an architectural level.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] These include breakpoints, watchpoints and instruction execution in a "Debug Mode"; similar facilities were also available with EmbeddedICE.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] Both "halt mode" and "monitor" mode debugging are supported.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] The actual transport mechanism used to access the debug facilities is not architecturally specified, but implementations generally include JTAG support.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] There is a separate ARM "CoreSight" debug architecture, which is not architecturally required by ARMv7 processors.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] The Debug Access Port (DAP) is an implementation of an ARM Debug Interface.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] There are two different supported implementations, the Serial Wire JTAG Debug Port (SWJ-DP) and the Serial Wire Debug Port (SW-DP).
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] CMSIS-DAP is a standard interface that describes how various debugging software on a host PC can communicate over USB to firmware running on a hardware debugger, which in turn talks over SWD or JTAG to a CoreSight-enabled ARM Cortex CPU.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] To improve the ARM architecture for digital signal processing and multimedia applications, DSP instructions were added to the instruction set.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] These are signified by an "E" in the name of the ARMv5TE and ARMv5TEJ architectures.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] The new instructions are common in digital signal processor (DSP) architectures.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] They include variations on signed multiply–accumulate, saturated add and subtract, and count leading zeros.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] First introduced in 1999, this extension of the core instruction set contrasted with ARM's earlier DSP coprocessor known as Piccolo, which employed a distinct, incompatible instruction set whose execution involved a separate program counter.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] Piccolo instructions employed a distinct register file of sixteen 32-bit registers, with some instructions combining registers for use as 48-bit accumulators and other instructions addressing 16-bit half-registers.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] Some instructions were able to operate on two such 16-bit values in parallel.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] Communication with the Piccolo register file involved *load to Piccolo* and *store from Piccolo* coprocessor instructions via two buffers of eight 32-bit entries.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] Described as reminiscent of other approaches, notably Hitachi's SH-DSP and Motorola's 68356, Piccolo did not employ dedicated local memory and relied on the bandwidth of the ARM core for DSP operand retrieval, impacting concurrent performance.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] Piccolo's distinct instruction set also proved not to be a "good compiler target".
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] Introduced in the ARMv6 architecture, this was a precursor to Advanced SIMD, also named Neon.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] Jazelle DBX (Direct Bytecode eXecution) is a technique that allows Java bytecode to be executed directly in the ARM architecture as a third execution state (and instruction set) alongside the existing ARM and Thumb-mode.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] Support for this state is signified by the "J" in the ARMv5TEJ architecture, and in ARM9EJ-S and ARM7EJ-S core names.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] Support for this state is required starting in ARMv6 (except for the ARMv7-M profile), though newer cores only include a trivial implementation that provides no hardware acceleration.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] To improve compiled code density, processors since the ARM7TDMI (released in 1994) have featured the *Thumb* compressed instruction set, which have their own state.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] (The "T" in "TDMI" indicates the Thumb feature.) When in this state, the processor executes the Thumb instruction set, a compact 16-bit encoding for a subset of the ARM instruction set.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] Most of the Thumb instructions are directly mapped to normal ARM instructions.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] The space saving comes from making some of the instruction operands implicit and limiting the number of possibilities compared to the ARM instructions executed in the ARM instruction set state.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] In Thumb, the 16-bit opcodes have less functionality.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] For example, only branches can be conditional, and many opcodes are restricted to accessing only half of all of the CPU's general-purpose registers.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] The shorter opcodes give improved code density overall, even though some operations require extra instructions.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] In situations where the memory port or bus width is constrained to less than 32 bits, the shorter Thumb opcodes allow increased performance compared with 32-bit ARM code, as less program code may need to be loaded into the processor over the constrained memory bandwidth.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] Unlike processor architectures with variable length (16- or 32-bit) instructions, such as the Cray-1 and Hitachi SuperH, the ARM and Thumb instruction sets exist independently of each other.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] Embedded hardware, such as the Game Boy Advance, typically have a small amount of RAM accessible with a full 32-bit datapath; the majority is accessed via a 16-bit or narrower secondary datapath.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] In this situation, it usually makes sense to compile Thumb code and hand-optimise a few of the most CPU-intensive sections using full 32-bit ARM instructions, placing these wider instructions into the 32-bit bus accessible memory.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] The first processor with a Thumb instruction decoder was the ARM7TDMI.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] All processors supporting 32-bit instruction sets, starting with ARM9, and including XScale, have included a Thumb instruction decoder.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] It includes instructions adopted from the Hitachi SuperH (1992), which was licensed by ARM.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] ARM's smallest processor families (Cortex M0 and M1) implement only the 16-bit Thumb instruction set for maximum performance in lowest cost applications.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] ARM processors that don't support 32-bit addressing also omit Thumb.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] Thumb-2 extends the Thumb instruction set with bit-field manipulation, table branches and conditional execution.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] At the same time, the ARM instruction set was extended to maintain equivalent functionality in both instruction sets.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] A new "Unified Assembly Language" (UAL) supports generation of either Thumb or ARM instructions from the same source code; versions of Thumb seen on ARMv7 processors are essentially as capable as ARM code (including the ability to write interrupt handlers).
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] This requires a bit of care, and use of a new "IT" (if-then) instruction, which permits up to four successive instructions to execute based on a tested condition, or on its inverse.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] When compiling into ARM code, this is ignored, but when compiling into Thumb it generates an actual instruction.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] All ARMv7 chips support the Thumb instruction set.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] All chips in the Cortex-A series that support ARMv7, all Cortex-R series, and all ARM11 series support both "ARM instruction set state" and "Thumb instruction set state", while chips in the Cortex-M series support only the Thumb instruction set.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] New features provided by ThumbEE include automatic null pointer checks on every load and store instruction, an instruction to perform an array bounds check, and special instructions that call a handler.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] In addition, because it utilises Thumb-2 technology, ThumbEE provides access to registers r8–r15 (where the Jazelle/DBX Java VM state is held).
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] Handlers are small sections of frequently called code, commonly used to implement high level languages, such as allocating memory for a new object.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] These changes come from repurposing a handful of opcodes, and knowing the core is in the new ThumbEE state.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] On 23 November 2011, Arm deprecated any use of the ThumbEE instruction set, and Armv8 removes support for ThumbEE.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] Some devices such as the ARM Cortex-A8 have a cut-down *VFPLite* module instead of a full VFP module, and require roughly ten times more clock cycles per float operation.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] Pre-Armv8 architecture implemented floating-point/SIMD with the coprocessor interface.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] Other floating-point and/or SIMD units found in ARM-based processors using the coprocessor interface include FPA, FPE, iwMMXt, some of which were implemented in software by trapping but could have been implemented in hardware.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] They provide some of the same functionality as VFP but are not opcode-compatible with it.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] FPA10 also provides extended precision, but implements correct rounding (required by IEEE 754) only in single precision.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] An optional extension to the ARM instruction set in the ARMv5TE, ARMv5TEJ and ARMv6 architectures.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] Implemented on most Cortex-A8 and A9 ARMv7 processors.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] It is backward-compatible with VFPv2, except that it cannot trap floating-point exceptions.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] VFPv3 has 32 64-bit FPU registers as standard, adds VCVT instructions to convert between scalar, float and double, adds immediate mode to VMOV such that constants can be loaded into FPU registers.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] As above, but with only 16 64-bit FPU registers.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] Implemented on Cortex-A12 and A15 ARMv7 processors, Cortex-A7 optionally has VFPv4-D32 in the case of an FPU with Neon.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] As above, but it has only 16 64-bit FPU registers.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] Implemented on Cortex-A5 and A7 processors in the case of an FPU without Neon.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] Implemented on Cortex-M7 when single and double-precision floating-point core option exists.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] In Debian Linux and derivatives such as Ubuntu and Linux Mint, **armhf** (**ARM hard float**) refers to the ARMv7 architecture including the additional VFP3-D16 floating-point hardware extension (and Thumb-2) above.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] Software packages and cross-compiler tools use the armhf vs. arm/armel suffixes to differentiate.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] The *Advanced SIMD* extension (also known as *Neon* or "MPE" Media Processing Engine) is a combined 64- and 128-bit SIMD instruction set that provides standardised acceleration for media and signal processing applications.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] Neon is included in all Cortex-A8 devices, but is optional in Cortex-A9 devices.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] Neon can execute MP3 audio decoding on CPUs running at 10 MHz, and can run the GSM adaptive multi-rate (AMR) speech codec at 13 MHz.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] It features a comprehensive instruction set, separate register files, and independent execution hardware.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] Neon supports 8-, 16-, 32-, and 64-bit integer and single-precision (32-bit) floating-point data and SIMD operations for handling audio and video processing as well as graphics and gaming processing.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] In Neon, the SIMD supports up to 16 operations at the same time.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] The Neon hardware shares the same floating-point registers as used in VFP.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] Devices such as the ARM Cortex-A8 and Cortex-A9 support 128-bit vectors, but will execute with 64 bits at a time, whereas some more powerful CPUs such as Cortex-A15 can execute 128 bits at a time.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] A quirk of Neon in Armv7 devices is that it flushes all subnormal numbers to zero, and as a result the GCC compiler will not use it unless `-funsafe-math-optimizations`, which allows losing denormals, is turned on.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] "Enhanced" Neon defined since Armv8 does not have this quirk, but as of GCC 8.2 the same flag is still required to enable Neon instructions.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] On the other hand, GCC does consider Neon safe on AArch64 for Armv8.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] ProjectNe10 is ARM's first open-source project (from its inception; while they acquired an older project, now named Mbed TLS).
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] The Ne10 library is a set of common, useful functions written in both Neon and C (for compatibility).
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] The library was created to allow developers to use Neon optimisations without learning Neon, but it also serves as a set of highly optimised Neon intrinsic and assembly code examples for common DSP, arithmetic, and image processing routines.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] Helium is the M-Profile Vector Extension (MVE).
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] It adds more than 150 scalar and vector instructions.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] The Security Extensions, marketed as TrustZone Technology, is in ARMv6KZ and later application profile architectures.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] It provides a low-cost alternative to adding another dedicated security core to an SoC, by providing two virtual processors backed by hardware based access control.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] This lets the application core switch between two states, referred to as *worlds* (to reduce confusion with other names for capability domains), to prevent information leaking from the more trusted world (the *Secure world*) to the less trusted world (the *Normal world*).
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] This world switch is generally orthogonal to all other capabilities of the processor, thus each world can operate independently of the other while using the same core.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] Memory and peripherals are then made aware of the operating world of the core and may use this to provide access control to secrets and code on the device.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] Typically, a rich operating system is run in the less trusted world, with smaller security-specialised code in the more trusted world, aiming to reduce the attack surface.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] Typical applications include DRM functionality for controlling the use of media on ARM-based devices, and preventing any unapproved use of the device.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] In practice, since the specific implementation details of proprietary TrustZone implementations have not been publicly disclosed for review, it is unclear what level of assurance is provided for a given threat model, but they are not immune from attack.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] Open Virtualization is an open source implementation of the trusted world architecture for TrustZone.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] AMD has licensed and incorporated TrustZone technology into its Secure Processor Technology.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] AMD's APUs include a Cortex-A5 processor for handling secure processing, which is enabled in some, but not all products.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] In fact, the Cortex-A5 TrustZone core had been included in earlier AMD products, but was not enabled due to time constraints.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] Samsung Knox uses TrustZone for purposes such as detecting modifications to the kernel, storing certificates and attestating keys.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] The Security Extension, marketed as TrustZone for Armv8-M Technology, was introduced in the Armv8-M architecture.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] While containing similar concepts to TrustZone for Armv8-A, it has a different architectural design, as world switching is performed using branch instructions instead of using exceptions.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] It also supports safe interleaved interrupt handling from either world regardless of the current security state.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] Together these features provide low latency calls to the secure world and responsive interrupt handling.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] ARM provides a reference stack of secure world code in the form of Trusted Firmware for M and PSA Certified.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] As of ARMv6, the ARM architecture supports no-execute page protection, which is referred to as *XN*, for *eXecute Never*.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] The Large Physical Address Extension (LPAE), which extends the physical address size from 32 bits to 40 bits, was added to the Armv7-A architecture in 2011.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] The physical address size may be even larger in processors based on the 64-bit (Armv8-A) architecture.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] For example, it is 44 bits in Cortex-A75 and Cortex-A65AE.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] The **Armv8-R** and **Armv8-M** architectures, announced after the Armv8-A architecture, share some features with Armv8-A.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] However, Armv8-M does not include any 64-bit AArch64 instructions, and Armv8-R originally did not include any AArch64 instructions; those instructions were added to Armv8-R later.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] The Armv8.1-M architecture, announced in February 2019, is an enhancement of the Armv8-M architecture.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] Announced in October 2011, **Armv8-A** (often called ARMv8 while the Armv8-R is also available) represents a fundamental change to the ARM architecture.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] It supports two *Execution states*: a 64-bit state named *AArch64* and a 32-bit state named *AArch32*.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] In the AArch64 state, a new 64-bit *A64* instruction set is supported; in the AArch32 state, two instruction sets are supported: the original 32-bit instruction set, named *A32*, and the 32-bit Thumb-2 instruction set, named *T32*.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] AArch32 provides user-space compatibility with Armv7-A.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] The processor state can change on an Exception level change; this allows 32-bit applications to be executed in AArch32 state under a 64-bit OS whose kernel executes in AArch64 state, and allows a 32-bit OS to run in AArch32 state under the control of a 64-bit hypervisor running in AArch64 state.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] ARM announced their Cortex-A53 and Cortex-A57 cores on 30 October 2012.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] Apple was the first to release an Armv8-A compatible core in a consumer product (Apple A7 in iPhone 5S).
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] AppliedMicro, using an FPGA, was the first to demo Armv8-A.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] The first Armv8-A SoC from Samsung is the Exynos 5433 used in the Galaxy Note 4, which features two clusters of four Cortex-A57 and Cortex-A53 cores in a big.LITTLE configuration; but it will run only in AArch32 mode.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] To both AArch32 and AArch64, Armv8-A makes VFPv3/v4 and advanced SIMD (Neon) standard.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] It also adds cryptography instructions supporting AES, SHA-1/SHA-256 and finite field arithmetic.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] AArch64 was introduced in Armv8-A and its subsequent revision.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] AArch64 is not included in the 32-bit Armv8-R and Armv8-M architectures.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] An ARMv8-A processor can support one or both of AArch32 and AArch64; it may support AArch32 and AArch64 at lower Exception levels and only AArch64 at higher Exception levels.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] For example, the ARM Cortex-A32 supports only AArch32, the ARM Cortex-A34 supports only AArch64, and the ARM Cortex-A72 supports both AArch64 and AArch32.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] An ARMv9-A processor must support AArch64 at all Exception levels, and may support AArch32 at EL0.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] Optional AArch64 support was added to the Armv8-R profile, with the first ARM core implementing it being the Cortex-R82.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] Announced in March 2021, the updated architecture places a focus on secure execution and compartmentalisation.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] The first ARMv9-A processors were released later that year, including the Cortex-A510, Cortex-A710 and Cortex-X2.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] Arm SystemReady is a compliance program that helps ensure the interoperability of an operating system on Arm-based hardware from datacenter servers to industrial edge and IoT devices.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] The key building blocks of the program are the specifications for minimum hardware and firmware requirements that the operating systems and hypervisors can rely upon.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] These specifications are co-developed by Arm and its partners in the System Architecture Advisory Committee (SystemArchAC).
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] Architecture Compliance Suite (ACS) is the test tools that help to check the compliance of these specifications.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] The Arm SystemReady Requirements Specification documents the requirements of the certifications.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] This program was introduced by Arm in 2020 at the first DevSummit event.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] Its predecessor Arm ServerReady was introduced in 2018 at the Arm TechCon event.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] PSA Certified, formerly named Platform Security Architecture, is an architecture-agnostic security framework and evaluation scheme.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] It is intended to help secure Internet of things (IoT) devices built on system-on-a-chip (SoC) processors.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] It was introduced to increase security where a full trusted execution environment is too large or complex.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] The architecture was introduced by Arm in 2017 at the annual TechCon event.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] Although the scheme is architecture agnostic, it was first implemented on Arm Cortex-M processor cores intended for microcontroller use.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] PSA Certified includes freely available threat models and security analyses that demonstrate the process for deciding on security features in common IoT products.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] It also provides freely downloadable application programming interface (API) packages, architectural specifications, open-source firmware implementations, and related test suites.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] Following the development of the architecture security framework in 2017, the PSA Certified assurance scheme launched two years later at Embedded World in 2019.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] PSA Certified offers a multi-level security evaluation scheme for chip vendors, OS providers and IoT device makers.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] The Embedded World presentation introduced chip vendors to Level 1 Certification.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] A draft of Level 2 protection was presented at the same time.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] Level 2 certification became a usable standard in February 2020.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] The certification was created by PSA Joint Stakeholders to enable a security-by-design approach for a diverse set of IoT products.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] PSA Certified specifications are implementation and architecture agnostic, as a result they can be applied to any chip, software or device.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] The certification also removes industry fragmentation for IoT product manufacturers and developers.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] The first 32-bit ARM-based personal computer, the Acorn Archimedes, was originally intended to run an ambitious operating system called ARX.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] The machines shipped with RISC OS, which was also used on later ARM-based systems from Acorn and other vendors.
[src:simd-hardware/arm-architecture-family-p02] Some early Acorn machines were also able to run a Unix port called RISC iX.
[src:simd-hardware/flynn-s-taxonomy] The four initial classifications defined by Flynn are based upon the number of concurrent instruction (or control) streams and data streams available in the architecture.
[src:simd-hardware/flynn-s-taxonomy] Flynn defined three additional sub-categories of SIMD in 1972.
[src:simd-hardware/flynn-s-taxonomy] A sequential computer which exploits no parallelism in either the instruction or data streams.
[src:simd-hardware/flynn-s-taxonomy] Single control unit (CU) fetches a single instruction stream (IS) from memory.
[src:simd-hardware/flynn-s-taxonomy] The CU then generates appropriate control signals to direct a single processing element (PE) to operate on a single data stream (DS) i.e., one operation at a time.
[src:simd-hardware/flynn-s-taxonomy] Examples of SISD architectures are the traditional uniprocessor machines such as older personal computers (PCs) (by 2010, many PCs had multiple cores) and older mainframe computers.
[src:simd-hardware/flynn-s-taxonomy] A single instruction is simultaneously applied to multiple different data streams.
[src:simd-hardware/flynn-s-taxonomy] Instructions can be executed sequentially, such as by pipelining, or in parallel by multiple functional units.
[src:simd-hardware/flynn-s-taxonomy] The modern term for an array processor is "single instruction, multiple threads" (SIMT).
[src:simd-hardware/flynn-s-taxonomy] This is a distinct classification in Flynn's 1972 taxonomy, as a subcategory of SIMD.
[src:simd-hardware/flynn-s-taxonomy] It is identifiable by the parallel subelements having their own independent register file and memory (cache and data memory).
[src:simd-hardware/flynn-s-taxonomy] Flynn's original papers cite two historic examples of SIMT processors: SOLOMON and ILLIAC IV.
[src:simd-hardware/flynn-s-taxonomy] Nvidia commonly uses the term in its marketing materials and technical documents, where it argues for the novelty of its architecture.
[src:simd-hardware/flynn-s-taxonomy] SOLOMON predates Nvidia by more than 60 years.
[src:simd-hardware/flynn-s-taxonomy] Flynn's 1972 paper calls pipelined processors a form of "time-multiplexed" Array processing, where elements are read sequentially from memory, processed in (pipelined) stages, and written out, again sequentially to memory, from the last stage.
[src:simd-hardware/flynn-s-taxonomy] From this description (page 954) it is likely that Flynn was referring to vector chaining, and to memory-to-memory vector processors such as the TI ASC designed manufactured and sold between 1966 and 1973, and the CDC STAR-100 which had just been announced at the time of writing of Flynn's paper.
[src:simd-hardware/flynn-s-taxonomy] At the time that Flynn wrote his 1972 paper many systems were using main memory as the resource from which pipelines were reading and writing.
[src:simd-hardware/flynn-s-taxonomy] When the resource that all "pipelines" read and write from is the scalar register file rather than main memory, modern variants of SIMD result.
[src:simd-hardware/flynn-s-taxonomy] Examples include Altivec, NEON, and AVX.
[src:simd-hardware/flynn-s-taxonomy] An alternative name for this type of register-based SIMD is "packed SIMD" and another is SIMD within a register (SWAR).
[src:simd-hardware/flynn-s-taxonomy] The modern term for associative processor is analogous to cells of content-addressable memory each having their own processor.
[src:simd-hardware/flynn-s-taxonomy] The Linedancer, released in 2010, contained 4096 2-bit predicated SIMD ALUs, each with its own CAM, and was capable of 800 billion instructions per second.
[src:simd-hardware/flynn-s-taxonomy] Aspex's ASP associative array SIMT processor predates NVIDIA by 20 years.
[src:simd-hardware/flynn-s-taxonomy] There is some difficulty in classifying this processor according to Flynn's taxonomy as it had both associative processing capability and array processing, both under explicit programmer control.
[src:simd-hardware/flynn-s-taxonomy] Multiple instructions operate on one data stream.
[src:simd-hardware/flynn-s-taxonomy] This is an uncommon architecture which is generally used for fault tolerance.
[src:simd-hardware/flynn-s-taxonomy] Heterogeneous systems operate on the same data stream and must agree on the result.
[src:simd-hardware/flynn-s-taxonomy] Examples include the Space Shuttle flight control computer.
[src:simd-hardware/flynn-s-taxonomy] Multiple autonomous processors simultaneously execute different instructions on different data.
[src:simd-hardware/flynn-s-taxonomy] MIMD architectures include multi-core superscalar processors, and distributed systems, using either one shared memory space or a distributed memory space.
[src:simd-hardware/flynn-s-taxonomy] These four architectures are shown below visually.
[src:simd-hardware/flynn-s-taxonomy] As of 2006, all of the top 10 and most of the TOP500 supercomputers are based on a MIMD architecture.
[src:simd-hardware/flynn-s-taxonomy] Although these are not part of Flynn's work, some further divide the MIMD category into the two categories below, and even further subdivisions are sometimes considered.
[src:simd-hardware/flynn-s-taxonomy] Multiple autonomous processors simultaneously executing the same program (but at independent points, rather than in the lockstep that SIMD imposes) on different data.
[src:simd-hardware/flynn-s-taxonomy] Also termed *single process, multiple data* - the use of this terminology for SPMD is technically incorrect, as SPMD is a parallel execution model and assumes multiple cooperating processors executing a program.
[src:simd-hardware/flynn-s-taxonomy] SPMD is the most common style of explicit parallel programming.
[src:simd-hardware/flynn-s-taxonomy] The SPMD model and the term was proposed by Frederica Darema of the RP3 team.
[src:simd-hardware/flynn-s-taxonomy] Multiple autonomous processors simultaneously operating at least two independent programs.
[src:simd-hardware/flynn-s-taxonomy] In HPC contexts, such systems often pick one node to be the "host" ("the explicit host/node programming model") or "manager" (the "Manager/Worker" strategy), which runs one program that farms out data to all the other nodes which all run a second program.
[src:simd-hardware/flynn-s-taxonomy] Those other nodes then return their results directly to the manager.
[src:simd-hardware/flynn-s-taxonomy] An example of this would be the Sony PlayStation 3 game console, with its SPU/PPU processor.
[src:simd-hardware/flynn-s-taxonomy] For example, the make build system can build multiple dependencies in parallel, using target-dependent programs in addition to the make executable itself.
[src:simd-hardware/flynn-s-taxonomy] MPMD also often takes the form of pipelines.
[src:simd-hardware/flynn-s-taxonomy] A simple Unix shell command like `ls | grep "A" | more` launches three processes running separate programs in parallel with the output of one used as the input to the next.
[src:simd-hardware/flynn-s-taxonomy] These are both distinct from the explicit parallel programming used in HPC in that the individual programs are generic building blocks rather than implementing part of a specific parallel algorithm.
[src:simd-hardware/flynn-s-taxonomy] In the pipelining approach, the amount of available parallelism does not increase with the size of the data set.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] In computer science, **parallelism** and concurrency are two different things: a parallel program uses multiple CPU cores, each core performing a task independently.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] On the other hand, concurrency enables a program to deal with multiple tasks even on a single CPU core; the core switches between tasks (i.e. threads) without necessarily completing each one.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] A program can have both, neither or a combination of parallelism and concurrency characteristics.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Parallel computers can be roughly classified according to the level at which the hardware supports parallelism, with multi-core and multi-processor computers having multiple processing elements within a single machine, while clusters, MPPs, and grids use multiple computers to work on the same task.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Specialized parallel computer architectures are sometimes used alongside traditional processors, for accelerating specific tasks.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Communication and synchronization between the different subtasks are typically some of the greatest obstacles to getting optimal parallel program performance.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] A theoretical upper bound on the speed-up of a single program as a result of parallelization is given by Amdahl's law, which states that it is limited by the fraction of time for which the parallelization can be utilised.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Traditionally, computer software has been written for serial computation.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] To solve a problem, an algorithm is constructed and implemented as a serial stream of instructions.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] These instructions are executed on a central processing unit on one computer.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Only one instruction may execute at a time—after that instruction is finished, the next one is executed.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Parallel computing, on the other hand, uses multiple processing elements simultaneously to solve a problem.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] This is accomplished by breaking the problem into independent parts so that each processing element can execute its part of the algorithm simultaneously with the others.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] The processing elements can be diverse and include resources such as a single computer with multiple processors, several networked computers, specialized hardware, or any combination of the above.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Historically parallel computing was used for scientific computing and the simulation of scientific problems, particularly in the natural and engineering sciences, such as meteorology.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] This led to the design of parallel hardware and software, and high performance computing.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Frequency scaling was the dominant reason for improvements in computer performance from the mid-1980s until 2004.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] The runtime of a program is equal to the number of instructions multiplied by the average time per instruction.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Maintaining everything else constant, increasing the clock frequency decreases the average time it takes to execute an instruction.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] An increase in frequency thus decreases runtime for all compute-bound programs.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] However, power consumption *P* by a chip is given by the equation *P* = *C* × *V* 2 × *F*, where *C* is the capacitance being switched per clock cycle (proportional to the number of transistors whose inputs change), *V* is voltage, and *F* is the processor frequency (cycles per second).
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Increases in frequency increase the amount of power used in a processor.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Increasing processor power consumption led ultimately to Intel's May 8, 2004 cancellation of its Tejas and Jayhawk processors, which is generally cited as the end of frequency scaling as the dominant computer architecture paradigm.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] To deal with the problem of power consumption and overheating the major central processing unit (CPU or processor) manufacturers started to produce power efficient processors with multiple cores.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] The core is the computing unit of the processor and in multi-core processors each core is independent and can access the same memory concurrently.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Multi-core processors have brought parallel computing to desktop computers.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Thus parallelization of serial programs has become a mainstream programming task.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] In 2012 quad-core processors became standard for desktop computers, while servers had 10+ core processors.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Moore's law predicted that the number of cores per processor would double every 18–24 months.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] By 2023 some processors had over one hundred cores.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Some designs having a mix of performance and efficiency cores (such as ARM's big.LITTLE design) due to thermal and design constraints.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] An operating system can ensure that different tasks and user programs are run in parallel on the available cores.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] However, for a serial software program to take full advantage of the multi-core architecture the programmer needs to restructure and parallelize the code.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] A speed-up of application software runtime will no longer be achieved through frequency scaling, instead programmers will need to parallelize their software code to take advantage of the increasing computing power of multicore architectures.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Optimally, the speedup from parallelization would be linear—doubling the number of processing elements should halve the runtime, and doubling it a second time should again halve the runtime.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] However, very few parallel algorithms achieve optimal speedup.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Most of them have a near-linear speedup for small numbers of processing elements, which flattens out into a constant value for large numbers of processing elements.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] The maximum potential speedup of an overall system can be calculated by Amdahl's law.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Amdahl's Law indicates that optimal performance improvement is achieved by balancing enhancements to both parallelizable and non-parallelizable components of a task.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Furthermore, it reveals that increasing the number of processors yields diminishing returns, with negligible speedup gains beyond a certain point.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Amdahl's Law has limitations, including assumptions of fixed workload, neglecting inter-process communication and synchronization overheads, primarily focusing on computational aspect and ignoring extrinsic factors such as data persistence, I/O operations, and memory access overheads.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Gustafson's law and Universal Scalability Law give a more realistic assessment of the parallel performance.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Understanding data dependencies is fundamental in implementing parallel algorithms.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] No program can run more quickly than the longest chain of dependent calculations (known as the critical path), since calculations that depend upon prior calculations in the chain must be executed in order.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] However, most algorithms do not consist of just a long chain of dependent calculations; there are usually opportunities to execute independent calculations in parallel.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Let *P**i* and *P**j* be two program segments.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Bernstein's conditions describe when the two are independent and can be executed in parallel.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] For *P**i*, let *I**i* be all of the input variables and *O**i* the output variables, and likewise for *P**j*.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Violation of the first condition introduces a flow dependency, corresponding to the first segment producing a result used by the second segment.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] The second condition represents an anti-dependency, when the second segment produces a variable needed by the first segment.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] The third and final condition represents an output dependency: when two segments write to the same location, the result comes from the logically last executed segment.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] In this example, instruction 3 cannot be executed before (or even in parallel with) instruction 2, because instruction 3 uses a result from instruction 2.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] It violates condition 1, and thus introduces a flow dependency.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] In this example, there are no dependencies between the instructions, so they can all be run in parallel.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Bernstein's conditions do not allow memory to be shared between different processes.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] For that, some means of enforcing an ordering between accesses is necessary, such as semaphores, barriers or some other synchronization method.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Subtasks in a parallel program are often called threads.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Some parallel computer architectures use smaller, lightweight versions of threads known as fibers, while others use bigger versions known as processes.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] However, "threads" is generally accepted as a generic term for subtasks.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Threads will often need synchronized access to an object or other resource, for example when they must update a variable that is shared between them.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Without synchronization, the instructions between the two threads may be interleaved in any order.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] If instruction 1B is executed between 1A and 3A, or if instruction 1A is executed between 1B and 3B, the program will produce incorrect data.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] The programmer must use a lock to provide mutual exclusion.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] A lock is a programming language construct that allows one thread to take control of a variable and prevent other threads from reading or writing it, until that variable is unlocked.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] The thread holding the lock is free to execute its critical section (the section of a program that requires exclusive access to some variable), and to unlock the data when it is finished.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] One thread will successfully lock variable V, while the other thread will be locked out—unable to proceed until V is unlocked again.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] This guarantees correct execution of the program.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Locks may be necessary to ensure correct program execution when threads must serialize access to resources, but their use can greatly slow a program and may affect its reliability.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Locking multiple variables using non-atomic locks introduces the possibility of program deadlock.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] An atomic lock locks multiple variables all at once.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] If it cannot lock all of them, it does not lock any of them.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] If two threads each need to lock the same two variables using non-atomic locks, it is possible that one thread will lock one of them and the second thread will lock the second variable.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] In such a case, neither thread can complete, and deadlock results.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Many parallel programs require that their subtasks act in synchrony.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Barriers are typically implemented using a lock or a semaphore.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] One class of algorithms, known as lock-free and wait-free algorithms, altogether avoids the use of locks and barriers.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] However, this approach is generally difficult to implement and requires correctly designed data structures.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Not all parallelization results in speed-up.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Generally, as a task is split up into more and more threads, those threads spend an ever-increasing portion of their time communicating with each other or waiting on each other for access to resources.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Once the overhead from resource contention or communication dominates the time spent on other computation, further parallelization (that is, splitting the workload over even more threads) increases rather than decreases the amount of time required to finish.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] This problem, known as parallel slowdown, can be improved in some cases by software analysis and redesign.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Applications are often classified according to how often their subtasks need to synchronize or communicate with each other.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] An application exhibits fine-grained parallelism if its subtasks must communicate many times per second; it exhibits coarse-grained parallelism if they do not communicate many times per second, and it exhibits embarrassing parallelism if they rarely or never have to communicate.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Embarrassingly parallel applications are considered the easiest to parallelize.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Flynn created one of the earliest classification systems for parallel (and sequential) computers and programs, now known as Flynn's taxonomy.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Flynn classified programs and computers by whether they were operating using a single set or multiple sets of instructions, and whether or not those instructions were using a single set or multiple sets of data.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] The single-instruction-single-data (SISD) classification is equivalent to an entirely sequential program.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] The single-instruction-multiple-data (SIMD) classification is analogous to doing the same operation repeatedly over a large data set.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] This is commonly done in signal processing applications.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Multiple-instruction-single-data (MISD) is a rarely used classification.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] While computer architectures to deal with this were devised (such as systolic arrays), few applications that fit this class materialized.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Multiple-instruction-multiple-data (MIMD) programs are by far the most common type of parallel programs.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Hennessy, "Some machines are hybrids of these categories, of course, but this classic model has survived because it is simple, easy to understand, and gives a good first approximation.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Parallel computing can incur significant overhead in practice, primarily due to the costs associated with merging data from multiple processes.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Specifically, inter-process communication and synchronization can lead to overheads that are substantially higher—often by two or more orders of magnitude—compared to processing the same data on a single thread.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Therefore, the overall improvement should be carefully evaluated.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] From the advent of very-large-scale integration (VLSI) computer-chip fabrication technology in the 1970s until about 1986, speed-up in computer architecture was driven by doubling computer word size—the amount of information the processor can manipulate per cycle.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Increasing the word size reduces the number of instructions the processor must execute to perform an operation on variables whose sizes are greater than the length of the word.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Historically, 4-bit microprocessors were replaced with 8-bit, then 16-bit, then 32-bit microprocessors.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] This trend generally came to an end with the introduction of 32-bit processors, which has been a standard in general-purpose computing for two decades.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Not until the early 2000s, with the advent of x86-64 architectures, did 64-bit processors become commonplace.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] A computer program is, in essence, a stream of instructions executed by a processor.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Without instruction-level parallelism, a processor can only issue less than one instruction per clock cycle (IPC < 1).
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] These processors are known as *subscalar* processors.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] These instructions can be re-ordered and combined into groups which are then executed in parallel without changing the result of the program.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] This is known as instruction-level parallelism.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Advances in instruction-level parallelism dominated computer architecture from the mid-1980s until the mid-1990s.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] All modern processors have multi-stage instruction pipelines.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Each stage in the pipeline corresponds to a different action the processor performs on that instruction in that stage; a processor with an *N*-stage pipeline can have up to *N* different instructions at different stages of completion and thus can issue one instruction per clock cycle (IPC = 1).
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] These processors are known as *scalar* processors.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] The canonical example of a pipelined processor is a RISC processor, with five stages: instruction fetch (IF), instruction decode (ID), execute (EX), memory access (MEM), and register write back (WB).
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] The Pentium 4 processor had a 35-stage pipeline.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Most modern processors also have multiple execution units.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] They usually combine this feature with pipelining and thus can issue more than one instruction per clock cycle (IPC > 1).
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] These processors are known as *superscalar* processors.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Superscalar processors differ from multi-core processors in that the several execution units are not entire processors (i.e. processing units).
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Instructions can be grouped together only if there is no data dependency between them.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Scoreboarding and the Tomasulo algorithm (which is similar to scoreboarding but makes use of register renaming) are two of the most common techniques for implementing out-of-order execution and instruction-level parallelism.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Task parallelisms is the characteristic of a parallel program that "entirely different calculations can be performed on either the same or different sets of data".
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] This contrasts with data parallelism, where the same calculation is performed on the same or different sets of data.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Task parallelism involves the decomposition of a task into sub-tasks and then allocating each sub-task to a processor for execution.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] The processors would then execute these sub-tasks concurrently and often cooperatively.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Task parallelism does not usually scale with the size of a problem.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Superword level parallelism is a vectorization technique based on loop unrolling and basic block vectorization.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] It is distinct from loop vectorization algorithms in that it can exploit parallelism of inline code, such as manipulating coordinates, color channels or in loops unrolled by hand.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Main memory in a parallel computer is either shared memory (shared between all processing elements in a single address space), or distributed memory (in which each processing element has its own local address space).
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Distributed memory refers to the fact that the memory is logically distributed, but often implies that it is physically distributed as well.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Distributed shared memory and memory virtualization combine the two approaches, where the processing element has its own local memory and access to the memory on non-local processors.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Accesses to local memory are typically faster than accesses to non-local memory.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] On the supercomputers, distributed shared memory space can be implemented using the programming model such as PGAS.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] This model allows processes on one compute node to transparently access the remote memory of another compute node.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] All compute nodes are also connected to an external shared memory system via high-speed interconnect, such as Infiniband, this external shared memory system is known as burst buffer, which is typically built from arrays of non-volatile memory physically distributed across multiple I/O nodes.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Computer architectures in which each element of main memory can be accessed with equal latency and bandwidth are known as uniform memory access (UMA) systems.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Typically, that can be achieved only by a shared memory system, in which the memory is not physically distributed.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] A system that does not have this property is known as a non-uniform memory access (NUMA) architecture.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Distributed memory systems have non-uniform memory access.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Computer systems (with the exception of Groq's LPUs) make use of caches—small and fast memories located close to the processor which store temporary copies of memory values (nearby in both the physical and logical sense).
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Parallel computer systems have difficulties with caches that may store the same value in more than one location, with the possibility of incorrect program execution.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] These computers require a cache coherency system, which keeps track of cached values and strategically purges them, thus ensuring correct program execution.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Bus snooping is one of the most common methods for keeping track of which values are being accessed (and thus should be purged).
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Designing large, high-performance cache coherence systems is a very difficult problem in computer architecture.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] As a result, shared memory computer architectures do not scale and distributed memory systems do.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Parallel computers based on interconnected networks need to have some kind of routing to enable the passing of messages between nodes that are not directly connected.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] The medium used for communication between the processors is likely to be hierarchical in large multiprocessor machines.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Parallel computers can be roughly classified according to the level at which the hardware supports parallelism.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] This classification is broadly analogous to the distance between basic computing nodes.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] These are not mutually exclusive; for example, clusters of symmetric multiprocessors are relatively common.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] A multi-core processor is a processor that includes multiple processing units (called "cores") on the same chip.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] IBM's Cell microprocessor, designed for use in the Sony PlayStation 3, is a prominent multi-core processor.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Each core in a multi-core processor can potentially be superscalar as well—that is, on every clock cycle, each core can issue multiple instructions from one thread.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Simultaneous multithreading (of which Intel's Hyper-Threading is the best known) was an early form of pseudo-multi-coreism.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] A processor capable of concurrent multithreading includes multiple execution units in the same processing unit—that is it has a superscalar architecture—and can issue multiple instructions per clock cycle from *multiple* threads.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Temporal multithreading on the other hand includes a single execution unit in the same processing unit and can issue one instruction at a time from *multiple* threads.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] A symmetric multiprocessor (SMP) is a computer system with multiple identical processors that share memory and connect via a bus.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Bus contention prevents bus architectures from scaling.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] As a result, SMPs generally do not comprise more than 32 processors.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Because of the small size of the processors and the significant reduction in the requirements for bus bandwidth achieved by large caches, such symmetric multiprocessors are extremely cost-effective, provided that a sufficient amount of memory bandwidth exists.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] A distributed computer (also known as a distributed memory multiprocessor) is a distributed memory computer system in which the processing elements are connected by a network.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Distributed computers are highly scalable.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] The terms "concurrent computing", "parallel computing", and "distributed computing" have a lot of overlap, and no clear distinction exists between them.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] The same system may be characterized both as "parallel" and "distributed"; the processors in a typical distributed system run concurrently in parallel.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] A cluster is a group of loosely coupled computers that work together closely, so that in some respects they can be regarded as a single computer.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Clusters are composed of multiple standalone machines connected by a network.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] While machines in a cluster do not have to be symmetric, load balancing is more difficult if they are not.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] The most common type of cluster is the Beowulf cluster, which is a cluster implemented on multiple identical commercial off-the-shelf computers connected with a TCP/IP Ethernet local area network.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Beowulf technology was originally developed by Thomas Sterling and Donald Becker.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] 87% of all Top500 supercomputers are clusters.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] The remaining are Massively Parallel Processors, explained below.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Because grid computing systems (described below) can easily handle embarrassingly parallel problems, modern clusters are typically designed to handle more difficult problems—problems that require nodes to share intermediate results with each other more often.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] This requires a high bandwidth and, more importantly, a low-latency interconnection network.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Many historic and current supercomputers use customized high-performance network hardware specifically designed for cluster computing, such as the Cray Gemini network.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] As of 2014, most current supercomputers use some off-the-shelf standard network hardware, often Myrinet, InfiniBand, or Gigabit Ethernet.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] A massively parallel processor (MPP) is a single computer with many networked processors.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] MPPs have many of the same characteristics as clusters, but MPPs have specialized interconnect networks (whereas clusters use commodity hardware for networking).
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] MPPs also tend to be larger than clusters, typically having "far more" than 100 processors.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] In an MPP, "each CPU contains its own memory and copy of the operating system and application.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] IBM's Blue Gene/L, the fifth fastest supercomputer in the world according to the June 2009 TOP500 ranking, is an MPP.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Grid computing is the most distributed form of parallel computing.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] It makes use of computers communicating over the Internet to work on a given problem.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Because of the low bandwidth and extremely high latency available on the Internet, distributed computing typically deals only with embarrassingly parallel problems.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Most grid computing applications use middleware (software that sits between the operating system and the application to manage network resources and standardize the software interface).
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] The most common grid computing middleware is the Berkeley Open Infrastructure for Network Computing (BOINC).
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Often volunteer computing software makes use of "spare cycles", performing computations at times when a computer is idling.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] The ubiquity of the Internet and high-bandwidth networks enabled cloud computing, a model where massively parallel resources are provided as a service.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] This paradigm abstracts the underlying hardware, allowing users to access virtualized clusters for scalable workloads without managing physical infrastructure.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Modern distributed ledger protocols apply parallel computing principles to overcome the sequential bottlenecks of traditional blockchains.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] By sharding the state space, newer consensus architectures allow for "massively parallel transaction processing".
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] In this model, utilized by protocols such as Cerberus, independent transactions are treated as parallel tasks that can be executed simultaneously on different nodes, rather than being processed serially in a single global block.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Within parallel computing, there are specialized parallel devices that remain niche areas of interest.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] While not domain-specific, they tend to be applicable to only a few classes of parallel problems.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Reconfigurable computing is the use of a field-programmable gate array (FPGA) as a co-processor to a general-purpose computer.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] An FPGA is, in essence, a computer chip that can rewire itself for a given task.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] FPGAs can be programmed with hardware description languages such as VHDL or Verilog.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Several vendors have created C to HDL languages that attempt to emulate the syntax and semantics of the C programming language, with which most programmers are familiar.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] The best known C to HDL languages are Mitrion-C, Impulse C, and Handel-C.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Specific subsets of SystemC based on C++ can also be used for this purpose.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] AMD's decision to open its HyperTransport technology to third-party vendors has become the enabling technology for high-performance reconfigurable computing.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] General-purpose computing on graphics processing units (GPGPU) is a fairly recent trend in computer engineering research.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] GPUs are co-processors that have been heavily optimized for computer graphics processing.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Computer graphics processing is a field dominated by data parallel operations—particularly linear algebra matrix operations.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] In the early days, GPGPU programs used the normal graphics APIs for executing programs.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] However, several new programming languages and platforms have been built to do general purpose computation on GPUs with both Nvidia and AMD releasing programming environments with CUDA and Stream SDK respectively.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Other GPU programming languages include BrookGPU, PeakStream, and RapidMind.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Nvidia has also released specific products for computation in their Tesla series.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] The technology consortium Khronos Group has released the OpenCL specification, which is a framework for writing programs that execute across platforms consisting of CPUs and GPUs.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] AMD, Apple, Intel, Nvidia and others are supporting OpenCL.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Several application-specific integrated circuit (ASIC) approaches have been devised for dealing with parallel applications.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Because an ASIC is (by definition) specific to a given application, it can be fully optimized for that application.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] As a result, for a given application, an ASIC tends to outperform a general-purpose computer.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] However, ASICs are created by UV photolithography.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] This process requires a mask set, which can be extremely expensive.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] A mask set can cost over a million US dollars.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] (The smaller the transistors required for the chip, the more expensive the mask will be.) Meanwhile, performance increases in general-purpose computing over time (as described by Moore's law) tend to wipe out these gains in only one or two chip generations.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] High initial cost, and the tendency to be overtaken by Moore's-law-driven general-purpose computing, has rendered ASICs unfeasible for most parallel computing applications.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] One example is the PFLOPS RIKEN MDGRAPE-3 machine which uses custom ASICs for molecular dynamics simulation.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] A vector processor is a CPU or computer system that can execute the same instruction on large sets of data.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Vector processors have high-level operations that work on linear arrays of numbers or vectors.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] An example vector operation is *A* = *B* × *C*, where *A*, *B*, and *C* are each 64-element vectors of 64-bit floating-point numbers.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] They are closely related to Flynn's SIMD classification.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Cray computers became famous for their vector-processing computers in the 1970s and 1980s.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] However, vector processors—both as CPUs and as full computer systems—have generally disappeared.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Modern processor instruction sets do include some vector processing instructions, such as with Freescale Semiconductor's AltiVec and Intel's Streaming SIMD Extensions (SSE).
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Concurrent programming languages, libraries, APIs, and parallel programming models (such as algorithmic skeletons) have been created for programming parallel computers.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] These can generally be divided into classes based on the assumptions they make about the underlying memory architecture—shared memory, distributed memory, or shared distributed memory.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Shared memory programming languages communicate by manipulating shared memory variables.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Distributed memory uses message passing.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] POSIX Threads and OpenMP are two of the most widely used shared memory APIs, whereas Message Passing Interface (MPI) is the most widely used message-passing system API.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] One concept used in programming parallel programs is the future concept, where one part of a program promises to deliver a required datum to another part of a program at some future time.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Efforts to standardize parallel programming include an open standard called OpenHMPP for hybrid multi-core parallel programming.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] The OpenHMPP directive-based programming model offers a syntax to efficiently offload computations on hardware accelerators and to optimize data movement to/from the hardware memory using remote procedure calls.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] The rise of consumer GPUs has led to support for compute kernels, either in graphics APIs (referred to as compute shaders), in dedicated APIs (such as OpenCL), or in other language extensions.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Automatic parallelization of a sequential program by a compiler is the "holy grail" of parallel computing, especially with the aforementioned limit of processor frequency.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Despite decades of work by compiler researchers, automatic parallelization has had only limited success.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Mainstream parallel programming languages remain either explicitly parallel or (at best) partially implicit, in which a programmer gives the compiler directives for parallelization.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] A few fully implicit parallel programming languages exist—SISAL, Parallel Haskell, SequenceL, SystemC (for FPGAs), Mitrion-C, VHDL, and Verilog.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] As a computer system grows in complexity, the mean time between failures usually decreases.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Application checkpointing is a technique whereby the computer system takes a "snapshot" of the application—a record of all current resource allocations and variable states, akin to a core dump—; this information can be used to restore the program if the computer should fail.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Application checkpointing means that the program has to restart from only its last checkpoint rather than the beginning.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] While checkpointing provides benefits in a variety of situations, it is especially useful in highly parallel systems with a large number of processors used in high performance computing.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] As parallel computers become larger and faster, we are now able to solve problems that had previously taken too long to run.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Fields as varied as bioinformatics (for protein folding and sequence analysis) and economics have taken advantage of parallel computing.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Parallel computing can also be applied to the design of fault-tolerant computer systems, particularly via lockstep systems performing the same operation in parallel.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] This provides redundancy in case one component fails, and also allows automatic error detection and error correction if the results differ.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] These methods can be used to help prevent single-event upsets caused by transient errors.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Although additional measures may be required in embedded or specialized systems, this method can provide a cost-effective approach to achieve n-modular redundancy in commercial off-the-shelf systems.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] The origins of true (MIMD) parallelism go back to Luigi Federico Menabrea and his *Sketch of the Analytic Engine Invented by Charles Babbage*.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] In 1957, Compagnie des Machines Bull announced the first computer architecture specifically designed for parallelism, the Gamma 60.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] It utilized a fork-join model and a "Program Distributor" to dispatch and collect data to and from independent processing units connected to a central memory.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] In April 1958, Stanley Gill (Ferranti) discussed parallel programming and the need for branching and waiting.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Also in 1958, IBM researchers John Cocke and Daniel Slotnick discussed the use of parallelism in numerical calculations for the first time.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Burroughs Corporation introduced the D825 in 1962, a four-processor computer that accessed up to 16 memory modules through a crossbar switch.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] In 1967, Amdahl and Slotnick published a debate about the feasibility of parallel processing at American Federation of Information Processing Societies Conference.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] It was during this debate that Amdahl's law was coined to define the limit of speed-up due to parallelism.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] In 1969, Honeywell introduced its first Multics system, a symmetric multiprocessor system capable of running up to eight processors in parallel.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] C.mmp, a multi-processor project at Carnegie Mellon University in the 1970s, was among the first multiprocessors with more than a few processors.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] The first bus-connected multiprocessor with snooping caches was the Synapse N+1 in 1984.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] SIMD parallel computers can be traced back to the 1970s.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] The motivation behind early SIMD computers was to amortize the gate delay of the processor's control unit over multiple instructions.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] In 1964, Slotnick had proposed building a massively parallel computer for the Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] His design was funded by the US Air Force, which was the earliest SIMD parallel-computing effort, ILLIAC IV.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] The key to its design was a fairly high parallelism, with up to 256 processors, which allowed the machine to work on large datasets in what would later be known as vector processing.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] However, ILLIAC IV was called "the most infamous of supercomputers", because the project was only one-fourth completed, but took 11 years and cost almost four times the original estimate.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] When it was finally ready to run its first real application in 1976, it was outperformed by existing commercial supercomputers such as the Cray-1.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] In the early 1970s, at the MIT Computer Science and Artificial Intelligence Laboratory, Marvin Minsky and Seymour Papert started developing the *Society of Mind* theory, which views the biological brain as massively parallel computer.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] In 1986, Minsky published *The Society of Mind*, which claims that "mind is formed from many little agents, each mindless by itself".
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] The theory attempts to explain how what we call intelligence could be a product of the interaction of non-intelligent parts.
[src:simd-hardware/parallel-computing] Minsky says that the biggest source of ideas about the theory came from his work in trying to create a machine that uses a robotic arm, a video camera, and a computer to build with children's blocks.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] Such machines exploit data level parallelism, but not concurrency: there are simultaneous (parallel) computations, but each unit performs exactly the same instruction at any given moment (just with different data).
[src:simd-hardware/simd] A simple example is to add many pairs of numbers together, all of the SIMD units are performing an addition, but each one has different pairs of values to add.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] SIMD is especially applicable to common tasks such as adjusting the contrast in a digital image or adjusting the volume of digital audio.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] Most modern central processing unit (CPU) designs include SIMD instructions to improve the performance of multimedia use.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] In recent CPUs, SIMD units are tightly coupled with cache hierarchies and prefetch mechanisms, which minimize latency during large block operations.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] For instance, AVX-512-enabled processors can prefetch entire cache lines and apply fused multiply-add operations (FMA) in a single SIMD cycle.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] SIMD has three different subcategories in Flynn's 1972 Taxonomy, one of which is single instruction, multiple threads (SIMT).
[src:simd-hardware/simd] SIMT should not be confused with software threads or hardware threads, both of which are task time-sharing (time-slicing).
[src:simd-hardware/simd] SIMT is true simultaneous parallel hardware-level execution, such as in the ILLIAC IV.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] SIMD should not be confused with Vector processing, characterized by the Cray 1 and clarified in Duncan's taxonomy.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] The difference between SIMD and vector processors is primarily the presence of a Cray-style `SET VECTOR LENGTH` instruction.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] The first known operational use to date of SIMD within a register was the TX-2, in 1958.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] It was capable of 36-bit operations and two 18-bit or four 9-bit sub-word operations.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] The first commercial use of SIMD instructions was in the ILLIAC IV, which was completed in 1972.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] Vector supercomputers of the early 1970s such as the CDC Star-100 and the Texas Instruments ASC could operate on a "vector" of data with a single instruction.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] Vector processing was especially popularized by Cray in the 1970s and 1980s.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] Vector processing architectures are now considered separate from SIMD computers: Duncan's Taxonomy includes them whereas Flynn's Taxonomy does not, due to Flynn's work (1966, 1972) pre-dating the Cray-1 (1977).
[src:simd-hardware/simd] The complexity of Vector processors however inspired a simpler arrangement known as SIMD within a register.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] The first era of modern SIMD computers was characterized by massively parallel processing-style supercomputers such as the Thinking Machines Connection Machine CM-1 and CM-2.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] These computers had many limited-functionality processors that would work in parallel.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] For example, each of 65,536 single-bit processors in a Thinking Machines CM-2 would execute the same instruction at the same time, allowing, for instance, to logically combine 65,536 pairs of bits at a time, using a hypercube-connected network or processor-dedicated RAM to find its operands.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] Supercomputing moved away from the SIMD approach when inexpensive scalar multiple instruction, multiple data (MIMD) approaches based on commodity processors such as the Intel i860 XP became more powerful, and interest in SIMD waned.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] The current era of SIMD processors grew out of the desktop-computer market rather than the supercomputer market.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] As desktop processors became powerful enough to support real-time gaming and audio/video processing during the 1990s, demand grew for this type of computing power, and microprocessor vendors turned to SIMD to meet the demand.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] This resurgence also coincided with the rise of DirectX and OpenGL shader models, which heavily leveraged SIMD under the hood.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] The graphics APIs encouraged programmers to adopt data-parallel programming styles, indirectly accelerating SIMD adoption in desktop software.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] Hewlett-Packard introduced Multimedia Acceleration eXtensions (MAX) instructions into PA-RISC 1.1 desktops in 1994 to accelerate MPEG decoding.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] Sun Microsystems introduced SIMD integer instructions in its "VIS" instruction set extensions in 1995, in its UltraSPARC I microprocessor.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] MIPS followed suit with their similar MDMX system.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] The first widely deployed desktop SIMD was with Intel's MMX extensions to the x86 architecture in 1996.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] This sparked the introduction of the much more powerful AltiVec system in the Motorola PowerPC and IBM's POWER systems.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] Intel responded in 1999 by introducing the all-new SSE system.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] Since then, there have been several extensions to the SIMD instruction sets for both architectures.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] Advanced vector extensions AVX, AVX2 and AVX-512 are developed by Intel.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] AMD supports AVX, AVX2, and AVX-512 in their current products.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] With SIMD, an order of magnitude increase in code size is not uncommon, when compared to equivalent scalar or equivalent vector code, and an order of magnitude *or greater* effectiveness (work done per instruction) is achievable with Vector ISAs.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] ARM's Scalable Vector Extension takes another approach, known in Flynn's Taxonomy more commonly known today as "Predicated" (masked) SIMD.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] This approach is not as compact as vector processing but is still far better than non-predicated SIMD.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] Detailed comparative examples are given at Vector processor § Vector instruction example.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] Small-scale (64 or 128 bits) SIMD became popular on general-purpose CPUs in the early 1990s and continued through 1997 and later with Motion Video Instructions (MVI) for Alpha.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] Intel's AVX-512 SIMD instructions process 512 bits of data at once.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] The IBM, Sony, Toshiba co-developed Cell processor's Synergistic Processing Element's (SPE's) instruction set is heavily SIMD based.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] AMD GPUs since the TeraScale (microarchitecture) are SIMD-based, a feature that has remained in the 2020s microartectures RDNA and CDNA, with a layer of single instruction, multiple threads (SIMT) above.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] On the other hand, Nvidia's CUDA architectures use scalar cores with SIMT.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] Philips, now NXP, developed several SIMD processors named Xetal.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] The Xetal has 320 16-bit processor elements especially designed for vision tasks.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] Apple's M1 and M2 chips also incorporate SIMD units deeply integrated with their GPU and Neural Engine, using Apple-designed SIMD pipelines optimized for image filtering, convolution, and matrix multiplication.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] This unified memory architecture helps SIMD instructions operate on shared memory pools more efficiently.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] (The CPU part implements ordinary NEON).
[src:simd-hardware/simd] SIMD instructions are widely used to process 3D graphics, although modern graphics cards with embedded SIMD have largely taken over this task from the CPU.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] Some systems also include permute functions that re-pack elements inside vectors, making them especially useful for data processing and compression.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] The trend of general-purpose computing on GPUs (GPGPU) may lead to wider use of SIMD in the future.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] Recent compilers such as LLVM, GNU Compiler Collection (GCC), and Intel's ICC offer aggressive auto-vectoring options.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] Developers can often enable these with flags like `-O3` or `-ftree-vectorize`, which guide the compiler to restructure loops for SIMD compatibility.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] Adoption of SIMD systems in personal computer software was at first slow, due to a number of problems.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] One was that many of the early SIMD instruction sets tended to slow overall performance of the system due to the re-use of existing floating point registers.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] Other systems, like MMX and 3DNow!, offered support for data types that were not interesting to a wide audience and had expensive context switching instructions to switch between using the FPU and MMX registers.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] Compilers also often lacked support, requiring programmers to resort to assembly language coding.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] The introduction of 3DNow! by AMD and SSE by Intel confused matters somewhat, but today the system seems to have settled down (after AMD adopted SSE) and newer compilers should result in more SIMD-enabled software.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] Intel and AMD now both provide optimized math libraries that use SIMD instructions, and open source alternatives like libSIMD, SIMDx86 and SLEEF have started to appear (see also libm).
[src:simd-hardware/simd] Apple Computer had somewhat more success, even though they entered the SIMD market later than the rest.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] AltiVec offered a rich system and can be programmed using increasingly sophisticated compilers from Motorola, IBM and GNU, therefore assembly language programming is rarely needed.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] Additionally, many of the systems that would benefit from SIMD were supplied by Apple itself, for example iTunes and QuickTime.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] However, in 2006, Apple computers moved to Intel x86 processors.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] Apple's APIs and development tools (XCode) were modified to support SSE2 and SSE3 as well as AltiVec.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] Apple was the dominant purchaser of PowerPC chips from IBM and Freescale Semiconductor.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] Even though Apple has stopped using PowerPC processors in their products, further development of AltiVec is continued in several PowerPC and Power ISA designs from Freescale and IBM.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] It is common for publishers of the SIMD instruction sets to make their own C and C++ language extensions with intrinsic functions or special datatypes (with operator overloading) guaranteeing the generation of vector code.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] Intel, AltiVec, and ARM NEON provide extensions widely adopted by the compilers targeting their CPUs.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] The GNU C Compiler takes the extensions a step further by abstracting them into a universal interface that can be used on any platform by providing a way of defining SIMD datatypes.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] The LLVM Clang compiler also implements the feature, with an analogous interface defined in the IR.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] Rust's `packed_simd` crate (and the experimental `std::simd`) uses this interface, and so does Swift 2.0+.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] C++ has an experimental interface `std::experimental::simd` that works similarly to the GCC extension.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] For GCC and libstdc++, a wrapper library that builds on top of the GCC extension is available.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] The `System.Numerics.Vector` package, available on NuGet, implements SIMD datatypes.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] Java also has a new proposed API for SIMD instructions available in OpenJDK 17 in an incubator module.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] It also has a safe fallback mechanism on unsupported CPUs to simple loops.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] Instead of providing an SIMD datatype, compilers can also be hinted to auto-vectorize some loops, potentially taking some assertions about the lack of data dependency.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] This is not as flexible as manipulating SIMD variables directly, but is easier to use.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] OpenMP 4.0+ has a `#pragma omp simd` hint.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] This OpenMP interface has replaced a wide set of nonstandard extensions, including Cilk's `#pragma simd`, GCC's `#pragma GCC ivdep`, and many more.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] "SIMD everywhere", a collection of C/C++ headers implementing platform-specific intrinsics for other platforms (e.g.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] SSE intrinsics for ARM NEON), includes the use of platform-specific intrinsics, generic vector interfaces, and vectorization hints.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] It can be used as a "Rosetta Stone" for comparing these different SIMD programming paradigms.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] Another approach is SPMD: write a program that looks as if it operates only one element on the time, then have a compiler widen it to match the SIMD vector width.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] This is the approach used by graphics shaders and more recently adopted by CPU-oriented tools such as Intel IPSC.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] Consumer software is typically expected to work on a range of CPUs covering multiple generations, which could limit the programmer's ability to use new SIMD instructions to improve the computational performance of a program.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] The solution is to include multiple versions of the same code that uses either older or newer SIMD technologies, and pick one that best fits the user's CPU at run-time (dynamic dispatch).
[src:simd-hardware/simd] FMV, manually coded in assembly language, is quite commonly used in a number of performance-critical libraries such as glibc and libjpeg-turbo.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] Intel C++ Compiler, GNU Compiler Collection since GCC 6, and Clang since clang 7 allow for a simplified approach, with the compiler taking care of function duplication and selection.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] GCC and clang requires explicit `target_clones` labels in the code to "clone" functions, while ICC does so automatically (under the command-line option `/Qax`).
[src:simd-hardware/simd] The Rust programming language also supports FMV.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] The setup is similar to GCC and Clang in that the code defines what instruction sets to compile for, but cloning is manually done via inlining.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] As using FMV requires code modification on GCC and Clang, vendors more commonly use library multi-versioning: this is easier to achieve as only compiler switches need to be changed.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] Glibc supports LMV and this functionality is adopted by the Intel-backed Clear Linux project.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] In 2013 John McCutchan announced that he had created a high-performance interface to SIMD instruction sets for the Dart programming language, bringing the benefits of SIMD to web programs for the first time.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] Instances of these types are immutable and in optimized code are mapped directly to SIMD registers.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] Operations expressed in Dart typically are compiled into a single instruction without any overhead.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] This is similar to C and C++ intrinsics.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] Benchmarks for 4×4 matrix multiplication, 3D vertex transformation, and Mandelbrot set visualization show near 400% speedup compared to scalar code written in Dart.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] Intel announced at IDF 2013 that they were implementing McCutchan's specification for both V8 and SpiderMonkey.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] However, by 2017, SIMD.js was taken out of the ECMAScript standard queue in favor of pursuing a similar interface in WebAssembly.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] Support for SIMD was added to the WebAssembly 2.0 specification, which was finished on 2022 and became official in December 2024.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] LLVM's autovectoring, when compiling C or C++ to WebAssembly, can target WebAssembly SIMD to automatically make use of SIMD, while SIMD intrinsic are also available.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] It has generally proven difficult to find sustainable commercial applications for SIMD-only processors in general-purpose computing.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] One that has had some measure of success is the GAPP, which was developed by Lockheed Martin and taken to the commercial sector by their spin-off Teranex.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] A more ubiquitous application for SIMD is found in video games: nearly every modern video game console since 1998 has incorporated a SIMD processor somewhere in its architecture.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] The PlayStation 2 was unusual in that one of its vector-float units could function as an autonomous digital signal processor (DSP) executing its own instruction stream, or as a coprocessor driven by ordinary CPU instructions.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] 3D graphics applications tend to lend themselves well to SIMD processing as they rely heavily on operations with 4-dimensional vectors.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] Microsoft's Direct3D 9.0 now chooses at runtime processor-specific implementations of its own math operations, including the use of SIMD-capable instructions.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] A later processor that used vector processing is the Cell processor used in the PlayStation 3, which was developed by IBM in cooperation with Toshiba and Sony.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] It uses a number of SIMD processors (a non-uniform memory access (NUMA) architecture, each with independent local store and controlled by a general purpose CPU) and is geared towards the huge datasets required by 3D and video processing applications.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] It differs from traditional ISAs by being SIMD from the ground up with no separate scalar registers.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] Ziilabs produced an SIMD type processor for use on mobile devices, such as media players and mobile phones.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] Larger scale commercial SIMD processors are available from ClearSpeed Technology, Ltd. and Stream Processors, Inc.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] ClearSpeed's CSX600 (2004) has 96 cores each with two double-precision floating point units while the CSX700 (2008) has 192.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] Stream Processors is headed by computer architect Bill Dally.
[src:simd-hardware/simd] Their Storm-1 processor (2007) contains 80 SIMD cores controlled by a MIPS CPU.
[src:simd-hardware/streaming-simd-extensions] SSE contains 70 new instructions (65 unique mnemonics using 70 encodings), most of which work on single precision floating-point data.
[src:simd-hardware/streaming-simd-extensions] SIMD instructions can greatly increase performance when exactly the same operations are to be performed on multiple data objects.
[src:simd-hardware/streaming-simd-extensions] Typical applications are digital signal processing and graphics processing.
[src:simd-hardware/streaming-simd-extensions] Intel's first IA-32 SIMD effort was the MMX instruction set.
[src:simd-hardware/streaming-simd-extensions] MMX had two main problems: it re-used existing x87 floating-point registers making the CPUs unable to work on both floating-point and SIMD data at the same time, and it only worked on integers.
[src:simd-hardware/streaming-simd-extensions] SSE floating-point instructions operate on a new independent register set, the XMM registers, and adds a few integer instructions that work on MMX registers.
[src:simd-hardware/streaming-simd-extensions] SSE was subsequently expanded by Intel to SSE2, SSE3, SSSE3 and SSE4.
[src:simd-hardware/streaming-simd-extensions] Because it supports floating-point math, it had wider applications than MMX and became more popular.
[src:simd-hardware/streaming-simd-extensions] The addition of integer support in SSE2 made MMX largely redundant, though further performance increases can be attained in some situations by using MMX in parallel with SSE operations.
[src:simd-hardware/streaming-simd-extensions] SSE was originally called **Katmai New Instructions** (**KNI**), Katmai being the code name for the first Pentium III core revision.
[src:simd-hardware/streaming-simd-extensions] During the Katmai project Intel sought to distinguish it from its earlier product line, particularly its flagship Pentium II.
[src:simd-hardware/streaming-simd-extensions] It was later renamed **Internet Streaming SIMD Extensions** (**ISSE**), then SSE.
[src:simd-hardware/streaming-simd-extensions] AMD eventually added full support for SSE instructions (sometimes referred to as 3DNow!
[src:simd-hardware/streaming-simd-extensions] Professional) starting with its Athlon XP (Corvette and Palomino cores) and Duron (Morgan core) processors.
[src:simd-hardware/streaming-simd-extensions] SSE originally added eight new 128-bit registers known as `XMM0` through `XMM7`.
[src:simd-hardware/streaming-simd-extensions] The AMD64 extensions from AMD added a further eight registers `XMM8` through `XMM15`, and this extension is duplicated in the Intel 64 architecture.
[src:simd-hardware/streaming-simd-extensions] There is also a new 32-bit control/status register, `MXCSR`.
[src:simd-hardware/streaming-simd-extensions] The registers `XMM8` through `XMM15` are accessible only in 64-bit operating mode.
[src:simd-hardware/streaming-simd-extensions] Because these 128-bit registers are additional machine states that the operating system must preserve across task switches, they are disabled by default until the operating system explicitly enables them.
[src:simd-hardware/streaming-simd-extensions] This means that the OS must know how to use the `FXSAVE` and `FXRSTOR` instructions, which is the extended pair of instructions that can save all x86 and SSE register states at once.
[src:simd-hardware/streaming-simd-extensions] This support was quickly added to all major IA-32 operating systems.
[src:simd-hardware/streaming-simd-extensions] The first CPU to support SSE, the Pentium III, shared execution resources between SSE and the floating-point unit (FPU).
[src:simd-hardware/streaming-simd-extensions] While a compiled application can interleave FPU and SSE instructions side-by-side, the Pentium III will not issue an FPU and an SSE instruction in the same clock cycle.
[src:simd-hardware/streaming-simd-extensions] This limitation reduces the effectiveness of pipelining, but the separate XMM registers do allow SIMD and scalar floating-point operations to be mixed without the performance hit from explicit MMX/floating-point mode switching.
[src:simd-hardware/streaming-simd-extensions] SSE introduced both scalar and packed floating-point instructions.
[src:simd-hardware/streaming-simd-extensions] Floating operations are IEEE 754-1985 compliant, with the exception of `RSQRTSS`, which is not specified in the standard.
[src:simd-hardware/streaming-simd-extensions] The following simple example demonstrates the advantage of using SSE.
[src:simd-hardware/streaming-simd-extensions] Consider an operation like vector addition, which is used very often in computer graphics applications.
[src:simd-hardware/streaming-simd-extensions] To add two single precision, four-component vectors together using x86 requires four floating-point addition instructions.
[src:simd-hardware/streaming-simd-extensions] This corresponds to four x86 FADD instructions in the object code.
[src:simd-hardware/streaming-simd-extensions] On the other hand, as the following pseudo-code shows, a single 128-bit 'packed-add' instruction can replace the four scalar addition instructions.
